ube.com/watch?v=nl6DPgiFDZs Compendium of discourses and readings \"Love All Lives as Your Own\", discourses recorded November 9,1980 and September 30,1983, 28 min.]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ieuRORUoKFQ Video Discourse \"The Learning of an Ant Man\" May 18, 1975, St. Peter's Church, New York City, 83 min.]\n*[http://www.humanmedia.org/catalog/program.php?products_id=111 Interview with Bawa Muhaiyaddeen in Philadelphia on Kindred Spirits public radio show by David Freudberg]\n\n'''Other External Links'''\n*[http://www.mysticsaint.info/2007/05/coleman-barks-vision-of-bawa.html Coleman Bark's dream of Bawa Muhaiyaddeen]\n*[http://www.folkways.si.edu/albumdetails.aspx?itemid=1594 ''Into the Secret of the Heart by Guru Bawa Muhaiyaddeen'' record details at Smithsonian Folkways]\n\n{{Sufism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muhaiyaddeen, Bawa}}\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Sufis]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Muslims]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Sufi religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Sufi teachers]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:American people of Sri Lankan Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n", "name_user": "MilpitasMonster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bawa_Muhaiyaddeen"}
{"title_page": "Divya Bharti", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actress}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Divya Bharti\n| image              = Divya Bharti.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Bharti in 1993\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1974|02|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date |df=yes|1993|04|05|1974|2|25}} (age 19)\n| death_place        = [[Versova, Mumbai]]\n| death_cause        = Accidental fall\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Actress\n| image_caption      = Divya Bharti in 1992\n| height             = 5 feet 6 inches (168 cm)\n| yearsactive        = 1990\u20131993\n| spouse             = [[Sajid Nadiadwala]]<br><small>(1992 \u20131993; her death)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Divya Bharti''' (25 February 1974 \u2013 5 April 1993) was an Indian film actress, who starred in a number of commercially successful [[Hindi cinema|Hindi]] and [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] motion pictures in the early 1990s.Known for her acting versatility, vivacity and beauty, she is regarded as one of the most popular & highest paid actresses of her time.<ref>{{Cite Hindustan Times 05/04/20}} web|url=https://www.facebook.com/divyabhartifan16/photos/a.330992600764859/341645796366206/?type=3|title=Divya Bharti Fan Club|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>-->\n\nBharti aspired to a career in films at a young age and started to get offers at age 14, while she was doing some modeling assignments. After several unsuccessful attempts, she made her debut with a lead role in the successful [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] drama ''[[Bobbili Raja]]'' (1990) at age 16. After featuring in a number of high-grossing Telugu films, she progressed to [[Bollywood|Hindi cinema]] in 1992 with the action thriller ''[[Vishwatma]]''. Bharti went on to have commercial success, appearing in films such as ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' and ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]'', the latter of which led to her winning the [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Debut]].<ref name=\"actress\">{{cite news|title=Shah Rukh Khan's autobiography Twenty Years In A Decade to release soon|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_shah-rukh-khan-s-autobiography-twenty-years-in-a-decade-to-release-soon_1552261|accessdate=28 July 2012|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=7 June 2011}}</ref> She acted in over a dozen consistently-successful Hindi films over a year span, which is to date an unbroken record in [[Hindi cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/divya-bharti-created-world-record-1541276.html|title=Divya Bharti created world record|work=daily.bhaskar.com|accessdate=27 September 2015|date=12 November 2010}}</ref> \n\nBharti died on 5 April 1993, aged 19,<ref name=Rediff>{{cite web|title=Looking at stars who died young|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-death-anniversary-of-divya-bharti-and-kurt-cobain/20110405.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=27 December 2011|date=26 December 2011}}</ref> from head injuries sustained after falling off the balcony of her fifth-floor apartment at [[Versova, Mumbai]]. She was at a high-time in her career at the time of her death, and due to this had received significant speculation from the Indian film industry and audiences.<ref name=\"life on screen\">{{cite news|author=Chopra, Sonia|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-07/news-interviews/31300649_1_biopic-bollywood-debut-mystery|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|title=Divya's journey: The 'ageless' diva over the years|date=7 April 2008|accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The sad truth: Celebs who committed suicide|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/gallery/actresses-who-committed-suicide-jiah-khan-kuldeep-randhawa-divya-bharti-in-their-prime/10/11881.html|website=[[India Today]]|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nDivya Bharti was born in [[Bombay]] (present-day [[Mumbai]]) to Om Prakash Bharti, an insurance officer, and his wife, Meeta Bharti.<ref name=\"SaariCa\u1e6d\u1e6dop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa2009\">{{cite book|author1=Anil Saari|author2=P\u0101rtha Ca\u1e6d\u1e6dop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa|title=Hindi Cinema: An Insider's View|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dqzQOgAACAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-569584-7|page=222}}</ref> She had a younger brother named Kunal and one half-sister Poonam, who was the child of Bharti's father's first marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bollyspice.com/7597/remembering-divya-bharti|title=Remembering Divya Bharti|publisher=BollySpice|accessdate=17 August 2013|date=September 2006}}</ref> Actress [[Kainaat Arora]] is her second cousin.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/divya-bhartis-cousin-kainaat-arora-to-make-bollywood-debut-with-grand-masti-634510|title=Divya Bharti's cousin Kainaat Arora to make Bollywood debut with Grand Masti|publisher=Movies.ndtv.com|date=9 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe spoke [[Hindi]], [[English language|English]] and [[Marathi language|Marathi]] fluently. In her early years, Bharti was known for her bubbly personality<ref name=\"fpj\">{{cite news|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/weekend/four-bollywood-beauties-unsolved-death-mysteries/784073|title=Four Bollywood beauties unsolved death mysteries - Free Press Journal|work=www.freepressjournal.in|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> and for her doll-like looks.<ref name=\"toi\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/Bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/Bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/photostory/38140566.cms|title=Bollywood mysteries that remain unsolved even today - The Times of India|date=30 September 2014|work=The Times of India|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> Bharti studied at Maneckji Cooper High School in [[Juhu|Juhu, Mumbai]]. She was an average student and completed 9th standard before pursuing an acting career.<ref>{{cite news|quote= Divya, who can be arguably termed India's Greta Garbo...|url=http://divyabharti.tumblr.com/biography|title= Early Life of Divya Bharti|work=Divya Bharti Portal|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1988, Bharti was discovered by filmmaker Nandu Tolani. Upon seeing her, Tolani insisted on signing her for one of his films. At that time, Bharti was in the ninth standard (in ninth grade). She was originally scheduled to make her screen debut in ''[[Gunahon Ka Devta (1990 film)|Gunahon Ka Devta]]'' in 1988, but her role was cancelled.<ref name=\"Yashpal(journalist.)2006\">{{cite book|author1=Yashpal|author2=Anand (journalist)|title=Divya|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iyCOxf1_UWAC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1797-3|page=266}}</ref> Kirti Kumar noticed Bharti at a video library, and thus was eager to sign her for his project ''[[Radha Ka Sangam]]'' opposite [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]], as he was searching for a new face. Weeks later, Kumar met with Dilip Shankar and managed to release Bharti from her contract. After taking dancing and acting lessons for months to prepare for her role, Bharti was eventually dropped and replaced by [[Juhi Chawla]].<ref name=\"Yashpal(journalist.)2006\"/> Though the reasons remain unclear, it was speculated that Kumar's possessiveness over Bharti and her childish nature were the cause of her replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merepix.com/2013/12/remembering-actress-divya-bharti-rare-photos-videos.html|title=Remembering Actress Divya Bharti \u2013 Rare Photos & Videos|work=merepix.com|accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nBharti's career was stalled until [[D. Ramanaidu]], [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] film producer, offered her ''[[Bobbili Raja]]'' opposite his son [[Daggubati Venkatesh]]. Without hoping for success after experiencing many failures in [[Bollywood]], she commenced shooting in [[Andhra Pradesh]] for her screen debut. The film was released in the summer of 1990 and became a colossal hit.<ref name=\"Bharti1981\">{{cite book|author=Ma Satya Bharti|title=Death Comes Dancing: Celebrating Life With Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh|url=https://archive.org/details/deathcomesdancin00saty|url-access=registration|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=1981|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|isbn=978-0-7100-0705-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/deathcomesdancin00saty/page/183 183]}}</ref> ''Bobbili Raja'' remains to this day one of the most popular [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] movies. That same year, Bharti acted in only one [[Tamil language|Tamil]] film, ''[[Nila Penne]]'' opposite [[Anand (actor)|Anand]]. The film was critically and financially unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Bharti1981\"/>\n\nIn box office ratings, she figured next to [[Vijayshanti]]. In 1991, Bharti had back-to-back hits, including ''[[Rowdy Alludu]]'' and ''[[Assembly Rowdy]]'', opposite actors [[Chiranjeevi]] and [[Mohan Babu]].<ref>{{cite book|title=India today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=clRDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2002|publisher=Thomson Living Media India Ltd.|page=224}}</ref> Later that year, Bharti began filming [[A. Kodandarami Reddy]]'s action romance ''[[Dharma Kshetram]]'' under Sri Rajeev Productions. Bharti got to work with Telugu film actor [[Nandamuri Balakrishna]].<ref name=\"Outlook\">{{cite book|title=Outlook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0-kvAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|volume=43|date=19 June 2003|publisher=Hathway Investments Pvt Limited}}</ref>\n\nWhile Bharti celebrated her success in [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Bollywood]]'s top directors were eager to sign the [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] superstar for their upcoming films. Bharti's first [[Bollywood]] film was ''[[Vishwatma]]'' opposite [[Sunny Deol]], directed by [[Rajiv Rai]], and was released on 2 January 1992. The film was Super-Hit at the box office and gained Bharti wider recognition from the public as well as film critics.<ref name=\"JhaBachchan2005\">{{cite book|author1=Subhash K. Jha|author2=Amitabh Bachchan|title=The Essential Guide to Bollywood|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s1mVuJJPm3UC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 November 2005|publisher=Roli Books Private Limited|location=Mumbai|isbn=978-81-7436-378-7|page=275}}</ref> Notably, the music of the film was successful, especially the song \"Saat Samundar\", which became a favourite, and put Bharti in the limelight of Bollywood.<ref name=\"JhaBachchan2005\"/>\n\nA week later, Bharti's next film, [[Lawrence D'Souza]]'s romantic drama ''[[Dil Ka Kya Kasoor]]'', alongside [[Prithvi (actor)|Prithvi]] released. The film was not a box office success but was recognized for its music.<ref name=\"India today\">{{cite book|title=India today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iWpDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=1994|publisher=Thomson Living Media India Ltd.}}</ref> After the box office failure of the film, she was quoted as saying, \"I wanted to prove myself. But I've fallen flat on my face. Now, I have to begin my climb all over again. Yet, I'm positive that one day, success will be mine.\" (''Stardust'', March 1992).<ref name=\"Somaaya2007\">{{cite book|author=Bhawana Somaaya|title=Hema Malini: The Authorized Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhoIGQAACAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2007|publisher=Lotus Collection|isbn=978-81-7436-467-8 |page=320}}</ref>\nIn March 1992, [[David Dhawan]]'s ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' was released. It was popular with critics and was a box office hit in India,<ref name=\"career\">{{cite web |url= http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/divya-bharti-created-world-record-1541276.html |title=Divya Bharti created world record |date=12 November 2010 }}</ref> marking Bharti's first major hit in Bollywood. It also gave a big boost to [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]'s career and launched [[David Dhawan]] as an established director.<ref name=\"David Dhawan's work' \">{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-interview-with-rohit-dhawan/20110922.htm |title= I've been critical about my father David Dhawan's work'|work=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>\nShortly thereafter, Bharti achieved further success in [[Raj Kanwar]]'s ''[[Filmfare]]''- award-winning love story ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]''<ref name=\"Shah Rukh Khan Starrer Deewana' \">{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/filmmaker-raj-kanwar-passes-away/20120203.htm |title= movie that launched actors Shah Rukh Khan|work=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> starred veteran actor [[Rishi Kapoor]] and newcomer [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]], which is regarded as one of the biggest blockbuster hits of 1992. Her performance in ''Deewana'' was highly appreciated.<ref name=\"Fan-tastic fantasies\">{{cite news |url=http://www.asianage.com/books/fan-tastic-fantasies-633 |title= Kriti Kapoor lives in a self-inflicted shrine made for Divya Bharti|newspaper=[[The Asian Age]]|accessdate=3 March 2010}}</ref> She received a [[Lux Face of the Year]] title. Critics reported that Bharti belonged to a new breed of [[Hindi]] film actors who broke away from character stereotypes. Bharti and [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] won the [[Filmfare Award for Lux New Face of the Year]] and [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Debut]] respectively.<ref name=\"India today\"/> By July 1992, Bharti's work in ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]'' was said to have earned her more recognition.\n\nShe had several other Hindi releases that year, among them ''[[Jaan Se Pyaara]]'', which featured Bharti alongside [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] once again, ''[[Geet (1992 film)|Geet]]'' opposite [[Avinash Wadhawan]], ''[[Dushman Zamana]]'' alongside [[Armaan Kohli]] and ''[[Balwaan]]'' which marked the debut of [[Sunil Shetty]].<ref name=\"Dawar2006\">{{cite book|author=Ramesh Dawar|title=Bollywood Yesterday-Today-Tomorrow|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TO6Fmi8FraUC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Star Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-1-905863-01-3|page=144}}</ref> The latter being a low budget film, achieved moderate success. In October, [[Hema Malini]]'s ''[[Dil Aashna Hai]]'', which once again featured her opposite [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] was released, which didn't do as well at the box office. Divya's performance as a bar dancer who sets out to find her birth mother was however appreciated.<ref name=\"flaunted her well toned talent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amarujala.com/Cinema/Dream-Girl-Hema-Malini-become-Hidinba-2571-1.html |title=Malini-become-Hidinba |publisher=amarujala.Com |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303144558/http://www.amarujala.com/Cinema/Dream-Girl-Hema-Malini-become-Hidinba-2571-1.html |archivedate=3 March 2012 }}</ref> Bharti decided to act in one Telugu movie per year in order to not disappoint her Telugu audience. Thus, ''[[Chittamma Mogudu]]'' was released at the end of 1992, starring once again the popular couple of Bharti and [[Mohan Babu]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}The ensemble film ''[[Kshatriya (film)|Kshatriya]]'' in which she co-starred alongside [[Sunny Deol]], [[Sanjay Dutt]] and [[Raveena Tandon]] was the last film to be released during Bharti's lifetime on March 26, 1993.<ref name=\"GulzarNihalani2003\">{{cite book|author1=Gulzar|author2=Govind Nihalani|author3=Saibal Chatterjee|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2003|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7991-066-5|page=659}}</ref>\n\nBharti's sudden death on April 5, 1993 left several films incomplete. She was more than halfway through the filming of ''[[Laadla (1994 film)|Laadla]]'' at the time of her death and the film was reshot with [[Sridevi]] replacing her. She was replaced in several other films she had not completed such as ''[[Mohra]]'', ''[[Kartavya (1995 film)|Kartavya]]'', ''[[Vijaypath]]'', [[Dilwale (1994 film)|''Dilwale'']], and ''[[Andolan (1995 film)|Andolan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Rachit Gupta|title=Flashback Friday: Forever young - Divya Bharti|url=http://www.filmfare.com/features/flashback-friday-forever-young-divya-bharti-3370.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=filmfare.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Anjali Muthanna|title=What happens to incomplete films when actors die? - Times of India|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/What-happens-to-incomplete-films-when-actors-die/articleshow/26794860.cms|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=The Times of India|date=4 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Divya Bharti: Death remains unsolved mystery|url=http://www.jagran.com/entertainment/bollywood-divya-bharti-death-remains-unsolved-mystery-10164837.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Jagran|date=25 February 2013}}</ref> Some films which Bharti had not started shooting for were subsequently shelved, such as ''Parinaam'' with [[Akshay Kumar]], ''Do Kadam'' with [[Salman Khan]], ''Kanyadaan'' with Rishi Kapoor, ''Bajrang'' with [[Sunny Deol]] and ''Chal Pe Chal'' with [[Jackie Shroff]].\n\nShortly before her death, she had completed filming for ''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]]'' and ''[[Shatranj (1993 film)|Shatranj]]'' which were released posthumously several months later and achieved moderate success. Although she had completed filming her scenes for both films, a dubbing artist was used as she never got the chance to dub for the films. Her incomplete [[Telugu language|Telugu]] film ''[[Tholi Muddhu]]'' was partly completed by actress [[Rambha (actress)|Rambha]], who slightly resembled Bharti and hence was used as her body double to complete her remaining scenes and the film released in October 1993. She was also supposed to play the role of Bhavani in the Telugu film [[Allari Premikudu|''Allari Premikudu'']], but due to her sudden death her role was given to Rambha.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kavirayani |first1=Suresh |title=The dark side of showbiz spotlight |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/The-dark-side-of-showbiz-spotlight/articleshow/20426428.cms|work=The Times of India|accessdate=17 June 2016|date=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDivya Bharti met director-producer [[Sajid Nadiadwala]] through [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] at the shooting of ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'', and they were married on 10 May 1992.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0926\u093f\u0935\u094d\u092f\u093e \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940 \u0915\u0947 \u092e\u094c\u0924 \u0915\u0940 \u0905\u0938\u0932\u0940 \u0935\u091c\u0939 |url=https://www.newstrend.news/68072/bollywood-actress-divya-bharti-death-mystery/ |website=newstrend.news |publisher=Newstrend |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Divya and Sajid were married in a private ceremony, with the presence of her hairdresser-friend Sandhya, Sandhya's husband and a [[Qazi]] at Nadiadwala's Tulsi Buildings residence (in Mumbai).<ref name=ht>{{cite news|author1=Roshmila Bhattacharya|title=Too young to die|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/too-young-to-die/story-YJq1kkah1FcCqZSn7aDCsK.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Hindustan Times|date=24 April 2011}}</ref> She converted to [[Islam]] after her marriage and changed her name to Sana Nadiadwala.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Khalid Mohamed|title=After 23 Years, Divya Bharti\u2019s Death Still Remains a Mystery|url=http://www.thequint.com/entertainment/2016/04/04/divya-bharti-mysterious-death-sajid-nadiadwala-shah-rukh-khan-deewana-rishi-kapoor|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=The Quint}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PHOTOS: Who killed Divya Bharti ?|url=http://www.saharasamay.com/gallery/photo-gallery/entertainment-photogallery/photos-who-killed-divya-bharti-/676478779/5/31178.html#photo|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Sahara Samay}}</ref> Divya Bharti's Marriage with Sajid Nadiadwala was kept secret, so that it would not affect her prosperous film career, which was on peak at that time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bollywood mysteries that remain unsolved even today |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/photostory/38140566.cms |website=Times of India |publisher=Times of India |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0907\u0928 6 \u090f\u0915\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938\u0947\u0938 \u0928\u0947 \u091b\u093f\u092a\u093e\u0915\u0930 \u0930\u0916\u0940 \u0925\u0940 \u0905\u092a\u0928\u0940 \u0936\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u0915\u0940 \u0916\u092c\u0930 |url=https://www.newstrend.news/281778/bollywoods-secret-marriages/ |website=newstrend.news |publisher=Newstrend |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nIn the late evening hours of April 5, 1993, Bharti fell off the balcony window of her fifth-floor apartment in Tulsi Buildings, [[Versova, Mumbai|Versova]], [[Andheri West]] (Mumbai). When her guests [[Neeta Lulla]], Neeta's husband Shyam, Divya's maid Amrita, and neighbors realised what had happened, she was rushed in an ambulance to the emergency department at [[Cooper Hospital]] lying in a pool of blood, where she died. The immediate cause of death was stated as severe head injuries and internal bleeding. She was cremated on 7 April 1993 at the Vile Parle crematorium, Mumbai.<ref name=\"ht\" /><ref>{{cite news|author1=Farhana|url=http://www.filmfare.com/interviews/remembering-divya-bharti-12829.html|title=Remembering Divya Bharti|date=5 April 2016|work=filmfare.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> \n\nThe reason of her fatal fall was never established and several theories circulated in the media during that time, including falling under the influence of alcohol (she was believed to be a heavy drinker); being pushed by someone (suspects included people present at the apartment) \u2013 deliberately, accidentally or otherwise; Bharti's habit of doing thrilling activities; suicide; murder; and the involvement of her husband and [[Organised crime in India|underworld]] mafia.<ref name=\"fpj\" /><ref>{{cite news|author1=Neha Borkar|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/10-celebrities-who-died-under-mysterious-circumstances-230516.html|title=10 Celebrities Who Died Under Mysterious Circumstances|date=25 February 2015|work=indiatimes.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Priyanko Sarkar|url=http://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/bollywood/8845-10-bollywood-personalities-who-died-mysteriously.html|title=10 Bollywood Personalities Who Died Mysteriously|work=www.mensxp.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.saharasamay.com/gallery/photo-gallery/photos-who-killed-divya-bharti-/676478779/31176.html|title=PHOTOS: Who killed Divya Bharti ?|work=Sahara Samay|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> The investigation was closed in 1998 by [[Mumbai police]] and the reason of death was stated as an accidental death.<ref name=\"toi\" /> \n\n== Legacy ==\nHer death caused a major loss to [[Bollywood]] film industry. The directors & producers, with whom she worked cited that \"If she was alive, she would have been to this day the most successful Indian actress just after [[Sridevi]] & [[Madhuri Dixit]]\".  Talat Jani, who worked with her in ''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]],'' said that \" when in the morning, I came across the news that Divya had fallen to her death, I was immensely shocked. It seemed to me as if anyone has torn the [[Novel]] of Divya from the middle.\"\n\n[[Bollywood]] legend [[Dev Anand]] made a movie titled ''[[Chargesheet (film)|Chargesheet]]'' which was loosely based on her death and the mystery surrounding it and was released on 30 September 2011.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year !! Title !! Role !! Language !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1990\n|''[[Bobbili Raja]]''\n| Rani\n| [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| Debut film\n|-\n|''[[Nila Pennae]]''\n| Surya\n| [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| Debut Tamil film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1991\n|''[[Rowdy Alludu]]''\n|Rekha\n|rowspan=\"3\" |Telugu\n|\n|-\n|''Naa Ille Naa Swargam''\n|Lalitha\n|\n|-\n|''[[Assembly Rowdy]]''\n| Pooja\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |1992\n|''[[Vishwatma]]''\n| Kusum\n| rowspan=\"10\" |Hindi\n| Debut Hindi film\n|-\n|''[[Dil Ka Kya Kasoor]]''\n| Seema/Shalani Saxena\n|\n|-\n|''Andhaa Insaaf''\n|Payel\n|\n|-\n|''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]''\n| Divya Thapar\n|\n|-\n|''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]''\n| Kaajal\n|[[Filmfare Award for Lux New Face of the Year]]\n|-\n|''[[Jaan Se Pyaara]]''\n| Sharmila\n|\n|-\n|''[[Balwaan]]''\n| Deepa\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dushman Zamana]]''\n| Seema\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dil Aashna Hai]]''\n| Laila / Sitara\n|\n|-\n|''[[Geet (1992 film)|Geet]]''\n| Neha\n| \n|-\n|''[[Chittemma Mogudu]]''\n| Chittemma\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Telugu\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dharma Kshetram]]''\n| Mythili\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |1993\n|''[[Dil Hi To Hai (1993 film)|Dil Hi To Hai]]''\n| Bharati\n| Hindi\n|\n|-\n|''[[Kshatriya (film)|Kshatriya]]''\n| Tanvi Singh\n| Hindi\n| Last release during her lifetime\n|-\n|''[[Tholi Muddhu]]''\n| Divya\n| Telugu\n| Posthumous release; partly completed by South Indian actress [[Rambha (actress)|Rambha]]\n|-\n|''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]]''\n| Kajal\n| Hindi\n| Posthumous release\n|-\n|''[[Shatranj (film)|Shatranj]]''\n| Renu\n| Hindi\n| Last release after her death\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name| id=0080251 | name = Divya Bharti }}\n* [http://www.divyabhartiportal.com/ Official website of Divya Bharti]\n{{FilmfareAwardBestFemaleDebut}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bharti, Divya}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths from falls]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Tamil cinema]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian actress}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Divya Bharti\n| image              = Divya Bharti.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Bharti in 1993\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1974|02|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]]\n| death_date         = {{Death date |df=yes|1993|04|05|1974|2|25}} (age 19)\n| death_place        = [[Versova, Mumbai]]\n| death_cause        = Accidental fall\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Actress\n| image_caption      = Divya Bharti in 1992\n| height             = 5 feet 6 inches (168 cm)\n| yearsactive        = 1990\u20131993\n| spouse             = [[Sajid Nadiadwala]]<br><small>(1992 \u20131993; her death)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Divya Bharti''' (25 February 1974 \u2013 5 April 1993) was an Indian film actress, who starred in a number of commercially successful [[Hindi cinema|Hindi]] and [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] motion pictures in the early 1990s.<!--Known for her acting versatility, vivacity and beauty, she is regarded as one of the most popular & highest paid actresses of her time.<ref>{{Cite Hindustan Times 05/04/20}} web|url=https://www.facebook.com/divyabhartifan16/photos/a.330992600764859/341645796366206/?type=3|title=Divya Bharti Fan Club|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>-->\n\nBharti aspired to a career in films at a young age and started to get offers at age 14, while she was doing some modeling assignments. After several unsuccessful attempts, she made her debut with a lead role in the successful [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] drama ''[[Bobbili Raja]]'' (1990) at age 16. After featuring in a number of high-grossing Telugu films, she progressed to [[Bollywood|Hindi cinema]] in 1992 with the action thriller ''[[Vishwatma]]''. Bharti went on to have commercial success, appearing in films such as ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' and ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]'', the latter of which led to her winning the [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Debut]].<ref name=\"actress\">{{cite news|title=Shah Rukh Khan's autobiography Twenty Years In A Decade to release soon|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_shah-rukh-khan-s-autobiography-twenty-years-in-a-decade-to-release-soon_1552261|accessdate=28 July 2012|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=7 June 2011}}</ref> She acted in over a dozen consistently-successful Hindi films over a year span, which is to date an unbroken record in [[Hindi cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/divya-bharti-created-world-record-1541276.html|title=Divya Bharti created world record|work=daily.bhaskar.com|accessdate=27 September 2015|date=12 November 2010}}</ref> \n\nBharti died on 5 April 1993, aged 19,<ref name=Rediff>{{cite web|title=Looking at stars who died young|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-death-anniversary-of-divya-bharti-and-kurt-cobain/20110405.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=27 December 2011|date=26 December 2011}}</ref> from head injuries sustained after falling off the balcony of her fifth-floor apartment at [[Versova, Mumbai]]. She was at a high-time in her career at the time of her death, and due to this had received significant speculation from the Indian film industry and audiences.<ref name=\"life on screen\">{{cite news|author=Chopra, Sonia|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-07/news-interviews/31300649_1_biopic-bollywood-debut-mystery|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|title=Divya's journey: The 'ageless' diva over the years|date=7 April 2008|accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The sad truth: Celebs who committed suicide|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/gallery/actresses-who-committed-suicide-jiah-khan-kuldeep-randhawa-divya-bharti-in-their-prime/10/11881.html|website=[[India Today]]|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nDivya Bharti was born in [[Bombay]] (present-day [[Mumbai]]) to Om Prakash Bharti, an insurance officer, and his wife, Meeta Bharti.<ref name=\"SaariCa\u1e6d\u1e6dop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa2009\">{{cite book|author1=Anil Saari|author2=P\u0101rtha Ca\u1e6d\u1e6dop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa|title=Hindi Cinema: An Insider's View|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dqzQOgAACAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-569584-7|page=222}}</ref> She had a younger brother named Kunal and one half-sister Poonam, who was the child of Bharti's father's first marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bollyspice.com/7597/remembering-divya-bharti|title=Remembering Divya Bharti|publisher=BollySpice|accessdate=17 August 2013|date=September 2006}}</ref> Actress [[Kainaat Arora]] is her second cousin.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/divya-bhartis-cousin-kainaat-arora-to-make-bollywood-debut-with-grand-masti-634510|title=Divya Bharti's cousin Kainaat Arora to make Bollywood debut with Grand Masti|publisher=Movies.ndtv.com|date=9 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe spoke [[Hindi]], [[English language|English]] and [[Marathi language|Marathi]] fluently. In her early years, Bharti was known for her bubbly personality<ref name=\"fpj\">{{cite news|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/weekend/four-bollywood-beauties-unsolved-death-mysteries/784073|title=Four Bollywood beauties unsolved death mysteries - Free Press Journal|work=www.freepressjournal.in|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> and for her doll-like looks.<ref name=\"toi\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/Bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/Bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/photostory/38140566.cms|title=Bollywood mysteries that remain unsolved even today - The Times of India|date=30 September 2014|work=The Times of India|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> Bharti studied at Maneckji Cooper High School in [[Juhu|Juhu, Mumbai]]. She was an average student and completed 9th standard before pursuing an acting career.<ref>{{cite news|quote= Divya, who can be arguably termed India's Greta Garbo...|url=http://divyabharti.tumblr.com/biography|title= Early Life of Divya Bharti|work=Divya Bharti Portal|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1988, Bharti was discovered by filmmaker Nandu Tolani. Upon seeing her, Tolani insisted on signing her for one of his films. At that time, Bharti was in the ninth standard (in ninth grade). She was originally scheduled to make her screen debut in ''[[Gunahon Ka Devta (1990 film)|Gunahon Ka Devta]]'' in 1988, but her role was cancelled.<ref name=\"Yashpal(journalist.)2006\">{{cite book|author1=Yashpal|author2=Anand (journalist)|title=Divya|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iyCOxf1_UWAC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1797-3|page=266}}</ref> Kirti Kumar noticed Bharti at a video library, and thus was eager to sign her for his project ''[[Radha Ka Sangam]]'' opposite [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]], as he was searching for a new face. Weeks later, Kumar met with Dilip Shankar and managed to release Bharti from her contract. After taking dancing and acting lessons for months to prepare for her role, Bharti was eventually dropped and replaced by [[Juhi Chawla]].<ref name=\"Yashpal(journalist.)2006\"/> Though the reasons remain unclear, it was speculated that Kumar's possessiveness over Bharti and her childish nature were the cause of her replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merepix.com/2013/12/remembering-actress-divya-bharti-rare-photos-videos.html|title=Remembering Actress Divya Bharti \u2013 Rare Photos & Videos|work=merepix.com|accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nBharti's career was stalled until [[D. Ramanaidu]], [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] film producer, offered her ''[[Bobbili Raja]]'' opposite his son [[Daggubati Venkatesh]]. Without hoping for success after experiencing many failures in [[Bollywood]], she commenced shooting in [[Andhra Pradesh]] for her screen debut. The film was released in the summer of 1990 and became a colossal hit.<ref name=\"Bharti1981\">{{cite book|author=Ma Satya Bharti|title=Death Comes Dancing: Celebrating Life With Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh|url=https://archive.org/details/deathcomesdancin00saty|url-access=registration|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=1981|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|isbn=978-0-7100-0705-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/deathcomesdancin00saty/page/183 183]}}</ref> ''Bobbili Raja'' remains to this day one of the most popular [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] movies. That same year, Bharti acted in only one [[Tamil language|Tamil]] film, ''[[Nila Penne]]'' opposite [[Anand (actor)|Anand]]. The film was critically and financially unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Bharti1981\"/>\n\nIn box office ratings, she figured next to [[Vijayshanti]]. In 1991, Bharti had back-to-back hits, including ''[[Rowdy Alludu]]'' and ''[[Assembly Rowdy]]'', opposite actors [[Chiranjeevi]] and [[Mohan Babu]].<ref>{{cite book|title=India today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=clRDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2002|publisher=Thomson Living Media India Ltd.|page=224}}</ref> Later that year, Bharti began filming [[A. Kodandarami Reddy]]'s action romance ''[[Dharma Kshetram]]'' under Sri Rajeev Productions. Bharti got to work with Telugu film actor [[Nandamuri Balakrishna]].<ref name=\"Outlook\">{{cite book|title=Outlook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0-kvAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|volume=43|date=19 June 2003|publisher=Hathway Investments Pvt Limited}}</ref>\n\nWhile Bharti celebrated her success in [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Bollywood]]'s top directors were eager to sign the [[Cinema of Andhra Pradesh|Telugu]] superstar for their upcoming films. Bharti's first [[Bollywood]] film was ''[[Vishwatma]]'' opposite [[Sunny Deol]], directed by [[Rajiv Rai]], and was released on 2 January 1992. The film was Super-Hit at the box office and gained Bharti wider recognition from the public as well as film critics.<ref name=\"JhaBachchan2005\">{{cite book|author1=Subhash K. Jha|author2=Amitabh Bachchan|title=The Essential Guide to Bollywood|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s1mVuJJPm3UC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 November 2005|publisher=Roli Books Private Limited|location=Mumbai|isbn=978-81-7436-378-7|page=275}}</ref> Notably, the music of the film was successful, especially the song \"Saat Samundar\", which became a favourite, and put Bharti in the limelight of Bollywood.<ref name=\"JhaBachchan2005\"/>\n\nA week later, Bharti's next film, [[Lawrence D'Souza]]'s romantic drama ''[[Dil Ka Kya Kasoor]]'', alongside [[Prithvi (actor)|Prithvi]] released. The film was not a box office success but was recognized for its music.<ref name=\"India today\">{{cite book|title=India today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iWpDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=1994|publisher=Thomson Living Media India Ltd.}}</ref> After the box office failure of the film, she was quoted as saying, \"I wanted to prove myself. But I've fallen flat on my face. Now, I have to begin my climb all over again. Yet, I'm positive that one day, success will be mine.\" (''Stardust'', March 1992).<ref name=\"Somaaya2007\">{{cite book|author=Bhawana Somaaya|title=Hema Malini: The Authorized Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhoIGQAACAAJ|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2007|publisher=Lotus Collection|isbn=978-81-7436-467-8 |page=320}}</ref>\nIn March 1992, [[David Dhawan]]'s ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'' was released. It was popular with critics and was a box office hit in India,<ref name=\"career\">{{cite web |url= http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/divya-bharti-created-world-record-1541276.html |title=Divya Bharti created world record |date=12 November 2010 }}</ref> marking Bharti's first major hit in Bollywood. It also gave a big boost to [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]'s career and launched [[David Dhawan]] as an established director.<ref name=\"David Dhawan's work' \">{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-interview-with-rohit-dhawan/20110922.htm |title= I've been critical about my father David Dhawan's work'|work=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>\nShortly thereafter, Bharti achieved further success in [[Raj Kanwar]]'s ''[[Filmfare]]''- award-winning love story ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]''<ref name=\"Shah Rukh Khan Starrer Deewana' \">{{cite web |url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/filmmaker-raj-kanwar-passes-away/20120203.htm |title= movie that launched actors Shah Rukh Khan|work=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> starred veteran actor [[Rishi Kapoor]] and newcomer [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]], which is regarded as one of the biggest blockbuster hits of 1992. Her performance in ''Deewana'' was highly appreciated.<ref name=\"Fan-tastic fantasies\">{{cite news |url=http://www.asianage.com/books/fan-tastic-fantasies-633 |title= Kriti Kapoor lives in a self-inflicted shrine made for Divya Bharti|newspaper=[[The Asian Age]]|accessdate=3 March 2010}}</ref> She received a [[Lux Face of the Year]] title. Critics reported that Bharti belonged to a new breed of [[Hindi]] film actors who broke away from character stereotypes. Bharti and [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] won the [[Filmfare Award for Lux New Face of the Year]] and [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Debut]] respectively.<ref name=\"India today\"/> By July 1992, Bharti's work in ''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]'' was said to have earned her more recognition.\n\nShe had several other Hindi releases that year, among them ''[[Jaan Se Pyaara]]'', which featured Bharti alongside [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] once again, ''[[Geet (1992 film)|Geet]]'' opposite [[Avinash Wadhawan]], ''[[Dushman Zamana]]'' alongside [[Armaan Kohli]] and ''[[Balwaan]]'' which marked the debut of [[Sunil Shetty]].<ref name=\"Dawar2006\">{{cite book|author=Ramesh Dawar|title=Bollywood Yesterday-Today-Tomorrow|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TO6Fmi8FraUC|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Star Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-1-905863-01-3|page=144}}</ref> The latter being a low budget film, achieved moderate success. In October, [[Hema Malini]]'s ''[[Dil Aashna Hai]]'', which once again featured her opposite [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] was released, which didn't do as well at the box office. Divya's performance as a bar dancer who sets out to find her birth mother was however appreciated.<ref name=\"flaunted her well toned talent\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amarujala.com/Cinema/Dream-Girl-Hema-Malini-become-Hidinba-2571-1.html |title=Malini-become-Hidinba |publisher=amarujala.Com |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303144558/http://www.amarujala.com/Cinema/Dream-Girl-Hema-Malini-become-Hidinba-2571-1.html |archivedate=3 March 2012 }}</ref> Bharti decided to act in one Telugu movie per year in order to not disappoint her Telugu audience. Thus, ''[[Chittamma Mogudu]]'' was released at the end of 1992, starring once again the popular couple of Bharti and [[Mohan Babu]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}The ensemble film ''[[Kshatriya (film)|Kshatriya]]'' in which she co-starred alongside [[Sunny Deol]], [[Sanjay Dutt]] and [[Raveena Tandon]] was the last film to be released during Bharti's lifetime on March 26, 1993.<ref name=\"GulzarNihalani2003\">{{cite book|author1=Gulzar|author2=Govind Nihalani|author3=Saibal Chatterjee|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2003|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7991-066-5|page=659}}</ref>\n\nBharti's sudden death on April 5, 1993 left several films incomplete. She was more than halfway through the filming of ''[[Laadla (1994 film)|Laadla]]'' at the time of her death and the film was reshot with [[Sridevi]] replacing her. She was replaced in several other films she had not completed such as ''[[Mohra]]'', ''[[Kartavya (1995 film)|Kartavya]]'', ''[[Vijaypath]]'', [[Dilwale (1994 film)|''Dilwale'']], and ''[[Andolan (1995 film)|Andolan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Rachit Gupta|title=Flashback Friday: Forever young - Divya Bharti|url=http://www.filmfare.com/features/flashback-friday-forever-young-divya-bharti-3370.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=filmfare.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Anjali Muthanna|title=What happens to incomplete films when actors die? - Times of India|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/What-happens-to-incomplete-films-when-actors-die/articleshow/26794860.cms|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=The Times of India|date=4 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Divya Bharti: Death remains unsolved mystery|url=http://www.jagran.com/entertainment/bollywood-divya-bharti-death-remains-unsolved-mystery-10164837.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Jagran|date=25 February 2013}}</ref> Some films which Bharti had not started shooting for were subsequently shelved, such as ''Parinaam'' with [[Akshay Kumar]], ''Do Kadam'' with [[Salman Khan]], ''Kanyadaan'' with Rishi Kapoor, ''Bajrang'' with [[Sunny Deol]] and ''Chal Pe Chal'' with [[Jackie Shroff]].\n\nShortly before her death, she had completed filming for ''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]]'' and ''[[Shatranj (1993 film)|Shatranj]]'' which were released posthumously several months later and achieved moderate success. Although she had completed filming her scenes for both films, a dubbing artist was used as she never got the chance to dub for the films. Her incomplete [[Telugu language|Telugu]] film ''[[Tholi Muddhu]]'' was partly completed by actress [[Rambha (actress)|Rambha]], who slightly resembled Bharti and hence was used as her body double to complete her remaining scenes and the film released in October 1993. She was also supposed to play the role of Bhavani in the Telugu film [[Allari Premikudu|''Allari Premikudu'']], but due to her sudden death her role was given to Rambha.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kavirayani |first1=Suresh |title=The dark side of showbiz spotlight |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/The-dark-side-of-showbiz-spotlight/articleshow/20426428.cms|work=The Times of India|accessdate=17 June 2016|date=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDivya Bharti met director-producer [[Sajid Nadiadwala]] through [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] at the shooting of ''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]'', and they were married on 10 May 1992.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0926\u093f\u0935\u094d\u092f\u093e \u092d\u093e\u0930\u0924\u0940 \u0915\u0947 \u092e\u094c\u0924 \u0915\u0940 \u0905\u0938\u0932\u0940 \u0935\u091c\u0939 |url=https://www.newstrend.news/68072/bollywood-actress-divya-bharti-death-mystery/ |website=newstrend.news |publisher=Newstrend |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Divya and Sajid were married in a private ceremony, with the presence of her hairdresser-friend Sandhya, Sandhya's husband and a [[Qazi]] at Nadiadwala's Tulsi Buildings residence (in Mumbai).<ref name=ht>{{cite news|author1=Roshmila Bhattacharya|title=Too young to die|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/too-young-to-die/story-YJq1kkah1FcCqZSn7aDCsK.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Hindustan Times|date=24 April 2011}}</ref> She converted to [[Islam]] after her marriage and changed her name to Sana Nadiadwala.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Khalid Mohamed|title=After 23 Years, Divya Bharti\u2019s Death Still Remains a Mystery|url=http://www.thequint.com/entertainment/2016/04/04/divya-bharti-mysterious-death-sajid-nadiadwala-shah-rukh-khan-deewana-rishi-kapoor|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=The Quint}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PHOTOS: Who killed Divya Bharti ?|url=http://www.saharasamay.com/gallery/photo-gallery/entertainment-photogallery/photos-who-killed-divya-bharti-/676478779/5/31178.html#photo|accessdate=14 June 2016|work=Sahara Samay}}</ref> Divya Bharti's Marriage with Sajid Nadiadwala was kept secret, so that it would not affect her prosperous film career, which was on peak at that time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bollywood mysteries that remain unsolved even today |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/bollywood-mysteries-that-remain-unsolved-even-today/photostory/38140566.cms |website=Times of India |publisher=Times of India |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0907\u0928 6 \u090f\u0915\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938\u0947\u0938 \u0928\u0947 \u091b\u093f\u092a\u093e\u0915\u0930 \u0930\u0916\u0940 \u0925\u0940 \u0905\u092a\u0928\u0940 \u0936\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u0915\u0940 \u0916\u092c\u0930 |url=https://www.newstrend.news/281778/bollywoods-secret-marriages/ |website=newstrend.news |publisher=Newstrend |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nIn the late evening hours of April 5, 1993, Bharti fell off the balcony window of her fifth-floor apartment in Tulsi Buildings, [[Versova, Mumbai|Versova]], [[Andheri West]] (Mumbai). When her guests [[Neeta Lulla]], Neeta's husband Shyam, Divya's maid Amrita, and neighbors realised what had happened, she was rushed in an ambulance to the emergency department at [[Cooper Hospital]] lying in a pool of blood, where she died. The immediate cause of death was stated as severe head injuries and internal bleeding. She was cremated on 7 April 1993 at the Vile Parle crematorium, Mumbai.<ref name=\"ht\" /><ref>{{cite news|author1=Farhana|url=http://www.filmfare.com/interviews/remembering-divya-bharti-12829.html|title=Remembering Divya Bharti|date=5 April 2016|work=filmfare.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> \n\nThe reason of her fatal fall was never established and several theories circulated in the media during that time, including falling under the influence of alcohol (she was believed to be a heavy drinker); being pushed by someone (suspects included people present at the apartment) \u2013 deliberately, accidentally or otherwise; Bharti's habit of doing thrilling activities; suicide; murder; and the involvement of her husband and [[Organised crime in India|underworld]] mafia.<ref name=\"fpj\" /><ref>{{cite news|author1=Neha Borkar|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/10-celebrities-who-died-under-mysterious-circumstances-230516.html|title=10 Celebrities Who Died Under Mysterious Circumstances|date=25 February 2015|work=indiatimes.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Priyanko Sarkar|url=http://www.mensxp.com/entertainment/bollywood/8845-10-bollywood-personalities-who-died-mysteriously.html|title=10 Bollywood Personalities Who Died Mysteriously|work=www.mensxp.com|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.saharasamay.com/gallery/photo-gallery/photos-who-killed-divya-bharti-/676478779/31176.html|title=PHOTOS: Who killed Divya Bharti ?|work=Sahara Samay|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> The investigation was closed in 1998 by [[Mumbai police]] and the reason of death was stated as an accidental death.<ref name=\"toi\" /> \n\n== Legacy ==\nHer death caused a major loss to [[Bollywood]] film industry. The directors & producers, with whom she worked cited that \"If she was alive, she would have been to this day the most successful Indian actress just after [[Sridevi]] & [[Madhuri Dixit]]\".  Talat Jani, who worked with her in ''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]],'' said that \" when in the morning, I came across the news that Divya had fallen to her death, I was immensely shocked. It seemed to me as if anyone has torn the [[Novel]] of Divya from the middle.\"\n\n[[Bollywood]] legend [[Dev Anand]] made a movie titled ''[[Chargesheet (film)|Chargesheet]]'' which was loosely based on her death and the mystery surrounding it and was released on 30 September 2011.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year !! Title !! Role !! Language !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1990\n|''[[Bobbili Raja]]''\n| Rani\n| [[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n| Debut film\n|-\n|''[[Nila Pennae]]''\n| Surya\n| [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| Debut Tamil film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1991\n|''[[Rowdy Alludu]]''\n|Rekha\n|rowspan=\"3\" |Telugu\n|\n|-\n|''Naa Ille Naa Swargam''\n|Lalitha\n|\n|-\n|''[[Assembly Rowdy]]''\n| Pooja\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |1992\n|''[[Vishwatma]]''\n| Kusum\n| rowspan=\"10\" |Hindi\n| Debut Hindi film\n|-\n|''[[Dil Ka Kya Kasoor]]''\n| Seema/Shalani Saxena\n|\n|-\n|''Andhaa Insaaf''\n|Payel\n|\n|-\n|''[[Shola Aur Shabnam (1992 film)|Shola Aur Shabnam]]''\n| Divya Thapar\n|\n|-\n|''[[Deewana (1992 film)|Deewana]]''\n| Kaajal\n|[[Filmfare Award for Lux New Face of the Year]]\n|-\n|''[[Jaan Se Pyaara]]''\n| Sharmila\n|\n|-\n|''[[Balwaan]]''\n| Deepa\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dushman Zamana]]''\n| Seema\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dil Aashna Hai]]''\n| Laila / Sitara\n|\n|-\n|''[[Geet (1992 film)|Geet]]''\n| Neha\n| \n|-\n|''[[Chittemma Mogudu]]''\n| Chittemma\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Telugu\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dharma Kshetram]]''\n| Mythili\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |1993\n|''[[Dil Hi To Hai (1993 film)|Dil Hi To Hai]]''\n| Bharati\n| Hindi\n|\n|-\n|''[[Kshatriya (film)|Kshatriya]]''\n| Tanvi Singh\n| Hindi\n| Last release during her lifetime\n|-\n|''[[Tholi Muddhu]]''\n| Divya\n| Telugu\n| Posthumous release; partly completed by South Indian actress [[Rambha (actress)|Rambha]]\n|-\n|''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]]''\n| Kajal\n| Hindi\n| Posthumous release\n|-\n|''[[Shatranj (film)|Shatranj]]''\n| Renu\n| Hindi\n| Last release after her death\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name| id=0080251 | name = Divya Bharti }}\n* [http://www.divyabhartiportal.com/ Official website of Divya Bharti]\n{{FilmfareAwardBestFemaleDebut}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bharti, Divya}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths from falls]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Tamil cinema]]\n", "name_user": "Aligulla", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divya_Bharti"}
{"title_page": "The Talk (talk show)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Talk\n| image                    = The Talk logo.png\n| genre                    = [[Talk show]]\n| creator                  = [[Sara Gilbert]]\n| director                 = \n| presenter                = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Julie Chen]]\n* Sara Gilbert\n* [[Sharon Osbourne]]\n* [[Marissa Jaret Winokur]]\n* [[Leah Remini]]\n* [[Holly Robinson Peete]]\n* [[Aisha Tyler]]\n* [[Sheryl Underwood]]\n* [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]]\n* [[Carrie Ann Inaba]]\n* [[Marie Osmond]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Gregg Wattenberg]]\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 10\n| num_episodes             = 2,033 (as of January 10, 2020)<ref>{{cite web|title=''The Talk'' Episodes on CBS|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-talk/episodes-season-4/307541|work=TV Guide|accessdate=February 15, 2014}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2019}}\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = Sara Gilbert<br>Brad Bessey (2010\u201311)<br>Susan Winston (2011)<ref>{{cite web|title=Susan Winston Joins CBS' 'The Talk'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/susan-winston-joins-cbs-talk-181552|author=Lesley Goldberg|periodical=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Guggenheim Partners|Prometheus Global Media]]|date=April 22, 2011|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref><br>John Redmann (2010\u2013)<ref>{{cite web|title=New Exec Producer of CBS' 'The Talk' Out After Two Weeks|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/susan-winston-as-talk-exec-192902|author=Sofia M. Fernandez|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=May 28, 2011|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n| producer                 = \n| location                 = {{unbulleted list|[[CBS Studio Center]]|[[Studio City, California]]}}\n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 42 minutes\n| company                  = [[CBS Television Studios]]\n| distributor              = \n| network                  = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[high-definition television|HDTV]])\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2010|10|18}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| related                  = ''[[Loose Women]]''\n| website                  = http://www.cbs.com/shows/the_talk/\n| production_website       = \n}}\n\n'''''The Talk''''' is an<!--Do not add things like \"Emmy-Award winning\" or \"People's Choice Award winning,\" that is undue weight.--> [[United States|American]] [[talk show]] that debuted on October 18, 2010, as part of [[CBS]]'s [[CBS Daytime|daytime]] programming block.<ref name=\"cbs_order\">{{cite web|title=CBS Orders New Daytime Talk Show for Fall |url= http://www.cbspressexpress.com/div.php/cbs_entertainment/release?id=25604|website=CBS PressExpress|publisher=[[CBS]]|date=July 22, 2010|accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> The show was developed by actress and host [[Sara Gilbert]].\n\nThe show features [[Sharon Osbourne]], [[Sheryl Underwood]], [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]], [[Carrie Ann Inaba]] (who also serves as the show's moderator) and [[Marie Osmond]]. They discuss the day's latest headlines, while usually tying in the show's theme of motherhood or at least parenthood, such as by giving their opinions \"through the eyes of mothers.\" The show also contains celebrity interviews and segments for mothers and parents in general.\n\n''The Talk'' is broadcast before a live studio audience at the [[CBS Studio Center]] in [[Studio City, California]] each Monday through Friday at 11:00 a.m. [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific Time]], and airs live on most CBS [[owned-and-operated station]]s and [[network affiliate|affiliates]] in the [[Eastern United States|Eastern]] and [[Central United States]] at 2:00 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]]. The program is broadcast on [[broadcast delay|tape delay]] elsewhere from the [[Mountain Time Zone]] westward. The Friday shows are recorded on Thursday afternoons at 1:00&nbsp;pm PT for broadcast the next day. Friday shows are taped before the same studio audience in attendance for the earlier live Thursday broadcast.\n\n==Format==\n''The Talk'' has a format similar in style to [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]''.  The opening segment of the broadcast is known as \"Everybody Talks\" and usually runs a combined 12 to 25 minutes over multiple segments, depending on the number of stories featured and the number of guests.  It is followed by topical discussion segments, involves the five-female host panel discussing current news items, typically focusing on [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] headlines, offbeat stories, and celebrity news. The program also actively incorporates [[social media]] to allow viewers to provide their opinions on the stories discussed through [[Twitter]] (using the hashtag #EverybodyTalks, or alternately the abbreviated #EVBT).  In season five, the program began allowing viewers to use [[Instagram]] to record and upload videos using the aforementioned hashtags, with one or two videos being selected to air on the live broadcasts.<ref>{{cite press release|title=CBS's \"The Talk\" Kicks Off Season 5 Monday, Sept. 8!|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2014/09/02/cbss-the-talk-kicks-off-season-5-monday-sept-8-45010/20140902cbs01/|publisher=CBS|via=The Futon Critic|date=September 2, 2014|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn most editions, the \"Top Talker\" serves as the final segment of the topical discussion, featuring a rotating set of contributors - most of whom are correspondents/hosts of entertainment-related newsmagazine programs or magazines or hosts of local or syndicated radio programs - providing detailed analysis of a single trending, usually celebrity-related, story. Following the \"Everybody Talks\" segment, all five hosts interview one or two featured celebrity guests; most of these interviews are conducted at the set's roundtable. Musical performances are also occasionally included.\n\nThe show also regularly has a cooking segment two to four times each week, with two of the panelists - rotating between any combination of Chen, Underwood, Gilbert, or Osbourne - assisting in the preparation of the featured recipes with the guest chef. Product giveaways are also done once per week, as part of a segment showcasing fashion/beauty products and electronics that are given away to studio audience members for attending the show, and are often tied into online [[Deal of the day|flash sale]]s where the viewing audience can purchase the products offered at a reduced price.\n\nTo conclude the show through season 9, each episode signed-off with one of the co-hosts, primarily the moderator, saying \"Remember, it's always the right time to have ''The Talk!''\". With the start of season 10 the sign-off \"Let's Talk Tomorrow!\" or \"Let's Talk Later\" (used on Friday) is used.\n\n==Development==\nIn December 2009, CBS announced the cancellation of ''[[As the World Turns]]'' after 54 years, and was looking for a program to replace the long-running [[soap opera]] in its time slot. Sara Gilbert approached CBS about producing a pilot that would feature six women talking about the day's headlines with opinions told through \"the eyes of mothers.\"<ref name = Mothers />\n\nOn July 21, 2010, CBS announced that it had picked up the show (by then, given the title ''The Talk''), beating out several other contenders, including a cooking show featuring [[Emeril Lagasse]]; ''Say It Now'', a talk show featuring [[Valerie Bertinelli]] and [[Rove McManus]]; and a revamped version of the classic game show ''[[Pyramid (game show)|Pyramid]]'', hosted by [[Andy Richter]].<ref name=Mothers>{{cite web|title=Sara Gilbert talk show to replace veteran CBS soap|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/07/21/us-gilbert-idUSTRE66K5XA20100721|author=Georg Szalai|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=September 19, 2012|date=July 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the 4 weeks prior to the show's debut, new episodes of ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]'' and ''[[Let's Make a Deal]]'', as well as repeats of ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'', aired in the timeslot vacated by ''As the World Turns''.\n\n==Co-hosts==\n\n=== Timeline ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width:\"100%\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Co-host !!  colspan=10 style=text-align:center; | Seasons\n|-\n!! width=\"80\" | 1 !! width=\"80\" | 2 !! width=\"80\" | 3 !! width=\"80\" | 4 !! width=\"80\" | 5 !! width=\"80\"| 6 !! width=\"80\" | 7 !! width=\"80\" |8 !! width=\"80\" | 9 !! width=\"80\" | 10\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Julie Chen]]}} || colspan=\"8\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Sara Gilbert]]}} || colspan=\"9\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Sharon Osbourne]]}} || colspan=\"10\" {{yes|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Marissa Jaret Winokur]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"9\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Holly Robinson Peete]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"9\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Leah Remini]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"9\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Aisha Tyler]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"6\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"3\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Sheryl Underwood]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"9\" {{yes|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Eve (rapper)|Eve]]}} || colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"3\" {{yes|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Carrie Ann Inaba]]}} || colspan=\"8\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"2\" {{yes|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Marie Osmond]]}} || colspan=\"9\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"1\" {{yes|}}\n|}\n\n===Season 1===\nThe original panel consisted of [[Sara Gilbert]], known for her role on the TV series ''[[Roseanne]]''; [[Holly Robinson Peete]], known for her roles on the TV series ''[[21 Jump Street]]'' and ''[[Hangin' with Mr. Cooper]]''; [[Leah Remini]], known for her role as Carrie Heffernan in the 1998\u20132007 CBS sitcom ''[[The King of Queens]]''; ''[[Big Brother (U.S.)|Big Brother]]'' hostess [[Julie Chen]]; and former talk show hostess/''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|X Factor]]'' judge [[Sharon Osbourne]], the wife of rocker [[Ozzy Osbourne]]. [[Marissa Jaret Winokur]] was featured in an out-of-the studio position as the \"mother on the street,\" dealing with issues like taking her toddler on an airplane, talking with kids about sex, talking to parents about the \"[[Child development stage|terrible twos]]\" and other parental issues.\n\nOn January 14, 2011, Marissa Jaret Winokur reported that she would not be returning to the show in 2011. In an exclusive statement to ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', original executive producer Brad Bessey said of Winokur's departure, \"We think the world of Marissa as a creative talent, on-air personality and super mom. This is a mutual decision based on time, not talent.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Hairspray's Marissa Jaret Winokur Exits CBS' \"The Talk\"|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/146759-Hairsprays-Marissa-Jaret-Winokur-Exits-CBS-The-Talk|author=Adam Hetrick|periodical=[[Playbill]]|publisher=Philip S Birsh (Rights and Permissions)|date=January 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Marissa Jaret Winokur Leaves 'The Talk'|url=http://www.popeater.com/2011/01/15/marissa-jaret-winokur-leaves-the-talk/|author=Christine Fenno|website=PopEater|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]] ([[AOL]])|date=January 15, 2011|accessdate= April 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhen ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' resumed filming on March 2, 2011, Osbourne's daughter [[Kelly Osbourne]] began filling in for her on a substitute basis, as the show's first substitute host.\n\nOn August 26, 2011, it was announced that original co-host Leah Remini had been released from the show.<ref>{{cite web|title=It's Official: Leah Remini Is Leaving The Talk|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/moviestvmusic/news/its-official-leah-remini-is-leaving-the-talk-2011268|periodical=[[Us Magazine]]|publisher=[[Wenner Media]]|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=December 26, 2011}}</ref> On September 2, 2011, it was confirmed that Holly Robinson Peete had also been released from the show.<ref>{{cite web|title=Enough Talk: Holly Robinson Peete \"Officially\" Not Returning to Chatfest|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/261761/enough-talk-holly-robinson-peete-officially-not-returning-to-chatfest|author=Brandi Fowler|website=[[E!|E! Online]]|publisher=[[Comcast|Comcast Entertainment Group]]|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=December 26, 2011}}</ref> Sharon Osbourne eventually gave opinion on their dismissals in December 2011 on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', stating: \"Some people don't really know who they are, and you have to know who you are when you're in something like this. You can't pretend to be something you're not. You have to know your brand. You can't be all things to everyone.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Howard Stern Gets The Talk Hosts To Finally Talk About Holly Robinson Peete Leah Remini Diss|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/howard_stern_gets_talk_hosts_finally/280413#ixzz1lrlsRcpC|website=E! Online|publisher=Comcast Entertainment Group|date=December 13, 2011|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sharon Osbourne, Leah Remini in Twitter feud about 'King of Queens' actress' dismissal from 'The Talk'?|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/television/sharon-osbourne-leah-remini-twitter-feud-king-queens-actress-dismissal-talk-article-1.1040078?localLinksEnabled=false|author=Joyce Chen|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman|Daily News, L.P.]]|date=March 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Seasons 2\u20135===\nOn August 26, 2011, CBS announced that comedian [[Sheryl Underwood]] would join the panel as a co-host at the start of its second season; Underwood was officially added to the program on September 6, 2011, beginning with that season's premiere episode.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kris Jenner to guest co-host 'The Talk'|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2011/08/kris-jenner-to-guest-co-host-the-talk-/1|author=Ann Oldenburg|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Molly Shannon]] served as the (guest) co-host during the month of September 2011. Actress and comedian [[Aisha Tyler]]'s addition to the panel was announced on October 23, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aisha Tyler to Co-Host CBS' 'The Talk'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/aisha-tyler-the-talk-host-252298 |author=Kimberly Nordyke|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=October 23, 2011|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Season 6===\nOn October 12, 2016, the episode of ''The Talk'' aired special tributes to four CBS [[soap opera]]s such as ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' (March 26, 1973\u2013present), ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]'' (March 23, 1987\u2013present), ''[[As the World Turns]]'' (April 2, 1956 \u2013 September 17, 2010), and ''[[Guiding Light]]'' (June 30, 1952 \u2013 September 18, 2009).\n\n===Season 7\u20138===\nOn June 15, 2017, Aisha Tyler announced she would leave the series following the completion of the series' seventh season. She said she would return as a guest host and to promote her various projects. Her last show aired on August 4, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/06/15/aisha-tyler-leaving-talk/|title=Aisha Tyler Chokes Back Tears Announcing Her Exit From CBS' 'The Talk'|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/aisha-tyler-leaving-cbs-talk-1013879|title=Aisha Tyler Leaving CBS' 'The Talk'|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Swift|first1=Andy|title=Aisha Tyler Leaving CBS' ''The Talk'' \u2014 Watch Her Emotional Announcement|url=http://tvline.com/2017/06/15/aisha-tyler-leaving-the-talk-cbs-announcement/|website=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=June 15, 2017|location=United States|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref> The current hosts of ''The Talk'' auditioned ladies on air as \"dates\" to fill in Aisha's seat. At the start of the eighth season, some of the guest hosts included [[Carrie Ann Inaba]], [[Garcelle Beauvais]], [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]], [[Sasheer Zamata]] and [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]]. Eve was announced as the fifth permanent co-host on November 14, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/the-talk-eve-cohost-cbs-show-season-8-aisha-tyler-1202613967/|title=\u2018The Talk\u2019 Adds Eve as Permanent Co-Host Following Aisha Tyler Departure|website=Variety|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Season 9===\nIn a promo for the ninth season, it was revealed that all five co-hosts would return to the panel. However, Chen did not return to the show for the ninth season premiere amid sexual misconduct allegations against her husband [[Leslie Moonves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/julie-chen-leslie-moonves-the-talk-cbs-1202934476/|title=Julie Chen Absent From \u2018The Talk\u2019 Season 9 Premiere Amid Moonves Ouster|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Rebecca|last=Rubin|date=September 10, 2018|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref> Chen officially announced her departure from the talk show in a pre-taped message on Tuesday, September 18, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Iannucci |first1=Rebecca |last2=Swift |first2=Andy |title=''The Talk''{{'}}s Julie Chen Confirms Exit in Tearful Video Message: 'I Will Always Cherish the Memories' \u2014 Watch |url=https://tvline.com/2018/09/18/julie-chen-leaving-the-talk-watch-video-message-final-episode/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=September 18, 2018 |location=United States |date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/julie-chen-the-talk-exit-1202946749/|title=Julie Chen Officially Exits \u2018The Talk\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Rebecca|last=Rubin|date=September 18, 2018|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> On December 6, 2018, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' announced that Inaba had been chosen to join the show as a permanent co-host, with a projected January 2019 debut.<ref>{{cite news |last=Otterson |first=Joe |title=Carrie Ann Inaba to Permanently Replace Julie Chen on ''The Talk'' (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/the-talk-carrie-ann-inaba-julie-chen-1203081973/ |accessdate=December 7, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=December 6, 2018 |location=United States |language=en}}</ref> Inaba officially joined the show on January 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last=de Moraes|first=Lisa|title=CBS Makes It Official: Carrie Ann Inaba Debuts as Julie Chen Replacement on ''The Talk''|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/carrie-ann-inaba-official-debut-julie-chen-replacement-the-talk-1202527925/|accessdate=January 2, 2019|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the April 9, 2019, episode, Gilbert announced she would depart the talk show at the conclusion of its ninth season; she cited acting opportunities and her desire to produce other projects as the reason for her departure;<ref>{{cite web |last=Iannucci |first=Rebecca |title=Sara Gilbert Leaving ''The Talk'' |url=https://tvline.com/2019/04/09/sara-gilbert-leaving-the-talk-video/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=April 9, 2019 |location=United States |date=April 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Harnick |first=Chris |title=Sara Gilbert Leaving ''The Talk'' After Nine Seasons |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1031071/sara-gilbert-leaving-the-talk-after-nine-seasons |website=[[E! Online]] |publisher=[[NBCUniversal]] |accessdate=April 9, 2019 |location=United States |date=April 9, 2019}}</ref> her final episode aired on August 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last=Swift |first=Andy |title=Sara Gilbert's Last Day on ''The Talk'': Watch Her Emotional Goodbye |url=https://tvline.com/2019/08/02/the-talk-sara-gilbert-leaves-watch-video-last-episode/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |location=United States |language=en |date=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Season 10===\nThe tenth season premiered on September 9, 2019, with [[Marie Osmond]] replacing Gilbert as co-host.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rice |first=Lynette |title=''The Talk'' recruits Marie Osmond to replace Sara Gilbert |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/05/07/the-talk-marie-osmond-replacing-sara-gilbert/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |location=United States |date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Yang |first=Rachel |title=''The Talk'' Sets Marie Osmond to Replace Sara Gilbert as Host |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/the-talk-sets-marie-osmond-replace-sara-gilbert-host-1203207739/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |location=United States |date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to Osmond's addition, a brand-new, state-of-the-art set was unveiled.<ref>{{cite web |last=Webb Mitovich |first=Matt |title=''The Talk'' Video Teases 'Two New Faces' \u2014 Including Sharon's Latest Facelift! |url=https://tvline.com/2019/09/05/the-talk-season-10-video-sharon-osbourne-facelift-marie-osmond-host/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=September 9, 2019 |location=United States |language=en |date=September 5, 2019}}</ref> In March 2020 the show was scheduled to broadcast without an audience due to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Covid-19]] [[pandemic]] but CBS later decided to stop the show all together out of an abundance of caution. The show was quickly revamped as The Talk @Home and began broadcast using the Zoom video platform featuring each host from their own homes.\n\n==Notable events==\n{{cleanup section|reason=some events are not notable|date=May 2017}}\n\n===Season premieres===\nThe first week of shows featured several celebrity guests, including model [[Christie Brinkley]], singer/actress [[Jennifer Lopez]], actress/director [[Chandra Wilson]], actress/author [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], and former South Carolina first lady [[Jenny Sanford]].<ref name=\"fancast_firstweekguests\">{{cite web|title=CBS\u2019 \u2018The Talk\u2019 Unveils First Week of High-Profile Guests|url=http://www.fancast.com/blogs/2010/tv-news/cbs-the-talk-unveils-first-week-of-high-profile-guests/|author=Tracy Phillips|website=Fancast|publisher=Comcast Interactive Media, LLC.|accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe third-season premiere (aired on September 10, 2012) featured all five co-hosts, as well as members of the studio audience, without their make-up and dressed in robes during the broadcast; all of the co-hosts were also shown beside pictures of themselves with make-up. The guests for that edition, who also participated in the stunt, were [[Jamie Lee Curtis]]; [[Michelle Stafford]] and [[Melody Thomas Scott]] of ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''; and [[Katherine Kelly Lang]] of ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Women of The Talk Go Makeup-Free|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/the-talk-hosts-no-makeup-1052851/|author=Sadie Gennis|website=[[TV Guide]]|publisher=Open Gate Capital|date=September 11, 2012|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Women of 'The Talk' go makeup-free -- VIDEO|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2012/09/10/women-of-the-talk-go-makeup-free-video|author=Lynette Rice|periodical=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=September 10, 2012|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe premiere weeks of the fourth and fifth seasons (September 9 to 13, 2013 and September 8 to 12, 2014) featured \"''The Talk'' Tells All\", a daily feature on the season's first week of shows in which co-hosts Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler and Underwood revealed never-before-disclosed personal secrets on-air.<ref>{{cite press release|title='The Talk' Announces Season 4 Premiere Week Line-Up|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/09/05/the-talk-announces-season-4-premiere-week-line-up/201158/|author=Sara Bibel|website=TV by the Numbers|date=September 5, 2013|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeason six premiered on September 14, 2015 with a slightly new set design featuring three new large monitors with backdrops including palm trees and the [[Los Angeles]] skyline. Season seven premiered on September 12, 2016, with the same set. The hosts kicked off premiere week by unveiling answers to the viewers' biggest questions with a theme they called \"''The 7 Wonders of The Talk''.\" <ref>{{cite web|title=The Talk's Seventh Season Promises Laughter, Friendship, And Wonder|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/the_talk/news/1005783/the-talk-s-seventh-season-promises-laughter-friendship-and-wonder/|website=cbs.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===On-location editions===\nThe show made two trips to New York City during its second season, broadcasting live for one week on each trip. The first trip placed some audience members inside and some outside the studio.<ref>{{cite press release|title=\nCBS\u2019s \"The Talk\" Heads To New York City For A Week Of Shows To Air Dec. 12-16|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/12/08/cbs%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%9Cthe-talk%E2%80%9D-heads-to-new-york-city-for-a-week-of-shows-to-air-dec-12-16/113149/|website=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=December 8, 2011|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref> Beginning with the second trip, the show began to tape its New York City-based episodes in a studio at the [[CBS Broadcast Center]], similar in structure to its Los Angeles studio, with the audience members based within the soundstage. ''The Talk'' has done week-long broadcasts from New York City twice per season since then (usually during the February and May [[sweeps]] periods and in December), with the Thursday and Friday episodes being recorded on the same day as the Tuesday and Wednesday live broadcasts.<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS' 'The Talk' will move to New York for a week in May and compete with Barbara Walters' 'The View'|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/confidential/cbs-talk-moves-nyc-week-article-1.1316495|newspaper=New York Daily News|publisher=Daily News, L.P.|date=April 14, 2013|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref> The program's first set of New York City episodes in the third season (from December 10 to 14, 2012), featured a partnership with [[Toys for Tots]], asking all guests and audience members to bring a new unwrapped toy to donate to the charity.\n\nDuring the third season, ''The Talk'' broadcast a week of episodes from [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]] \u2013 site of [[Super Bowl XLVII]] - from January 28, 2013 to February 1, 2013, to help promote CBS's coverage of the [[National Football League]] championship game.\n\n===''The Talk After Dark''===\nFrom January 12 to 16, 2015, CBS broadcast a special second \"[[late night television|late night]]\" edition of ''The Talk'' \u2013 unofficially titled ''The Talk After Dark'' - which filled the 12:37&nbsp;a.m. Eastern timeslot normally occupied by ''[[The Late Late Show (CBS TV series)|The Late Late Show]]'' (which itself utilized [[List of The Late Late Show episodes (2015 guest hosts)|guest hosts]] on most other weeks in the four-month period between [[Craig Ferguson]]'s departure from ''The Late Late Show'' in December 2014 and the start of [[James Corden]]'s tenure as host of that program in March 2015). Recorded each afternoon that week before the studio audience in attendance for the earlier live daytime broadcasts for broadcast each night, the episodes featured a separate slate of guests and featured topics from the daytime editions, and featured a special [[house band]] exclusive to the late-night editions led by rock musician/songwriter [[Linda Perry]] (wife of series creator and co-host Sara Gilbert).<ref>{{cite web|title=CBS Taps \u2018The Talk\u2019 and Guest Hosts To Fill \u2018Late Late Show\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/cbs-taps-the-talk-and-guest-hosts-to-fill-late-late-show-1201365480/|author=Brian Steinberg|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=November 26, 2014|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Breaking News - Guests Announced for \"The Late Late Show\" with Guest Host Drew Carey (1/5-1/9) and After-Dark Edition of \"The Talk\" (1/12-1/16)|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2014/12/22/guests-announced-for-the-late-late-show-with-guest-host-drew-carey-1-5-1-9-and-after-dark-edition-of-the-talk-1-12-1-16-742210/20141222cbs01/|website=The Futon Critic|date=December 22, 2014|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===''The Talk: Keep Talking''===\nFrom March 15 to 16, 2018 ''The Talk'' aired two exclusive episodes on their Facebook page entitled ''Keep Talking'' as CBS broadcast the [[NCAA March Madness]] games on the aforementioned dates. This special edition featured all five co-hosts communicating with their Facebook fans asking them personal questions and advice for their own personal problems. Unlike a normal episode the topics are decided entirely by the fans. Both episodes are similar to ''[[The Real (talk show)|The Real]]'s'' online exclusive segments and both episodes are around four minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=You're Invited To \"Keep Talking!\"\n|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheTalkCBS/videos/1653734334663498/|website=Facebook|date=March 9, 2018|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Keep Talking: The Hosts' Pre-Show Rituals|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheTalkCBS/videos/1659254500778148/|website=Facebook|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Keep Talking: Dating Advice|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheTalkCBS/videos/1659260670777531/|website=Facebook|date=March 16, 2018|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===''The Talk: Chat Room''===\nCarrie Ann Inaba originally announced on the March 12, 2020 episode that due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] The Talk will be shot without an audience. After CBS forced production to shut down Inaba took matters into her own hands by hosting a daily Instagram live from her own house (at the same time when the show originally airs) under self quarantine. CBS greenlit Inaba's daily [[Instagram]] live (now including all five co-hosts) into ''The Talk: Chat Room'' as production was shut down. Guests on this version included [[Raven Symone]], [[Dr. Phil]], [[Olivia Newton-John]], [[The Bella Twins]] and [[Tyra Banks]].\n\n===''The Talk: @Home''===\nStarting March 30, 2020 the show will now be shot from each co-hosts (and guests) home via [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] also due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]]. [[Wayne Brady]] will be their first guest. Other guests will include [[Jaime Camil]], [[Pauley Perrette]], [[Dr. Oz]], [[Terry Crews]], [[Sean Hayes]] and [[Sebastian Maniscalco]].\n\n==Appearances in other media==\nOn March 14, 2016, all of ''The Talk'' hosts (including then host [[Aisha Tyler]]) made a cameo on ''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]'' in the episode \"Falling\" when [[Cat Grant]] (played by [[Calista Flockhart]]) made a guest appearance on ''The Talk''. On December 15, 2017, [[Julie Chen]] revealed that all of the current hosts of The Talk (including new co-host [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]]) will be featured on an episode of [[Jane the Virgin]] as themselves which was directed by [[Gina Rodriguez]]. On January 10, 2018, ''The Talk'' revealed on their Instagram and Snapchat stories they filmed their episode of ''Jane the Virgin'' on the set of ''The Talk'' right after filming the show for the aforementioned date. On February 9, 2018, Rodriguez made a guest appearance on the show to announce the episode featuring the ladies of ''The Talk'', called \"Chapter Seventy-Four\" would air that night.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Ratings===\nThe debut episode of ''The Talk'' was number one in its timeslot in 20 of the 56 markets.<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite web|last=Seidman|first=Robert|title=Premiere of CBS's 'The Talk' 24% Better than October 2009 Avg for 'As the World Turns'|url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2010/10/19/premiere-of-cbss-the-talk-24-better-than-october-2009-avg-for-as-the-world-turns/68697|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> As of October 2011, ''The Talk'' averaged 1.83 million viewers per episode,<ref>{{cite web|last=Seidman|first=Robert|title=CBS Renews 'The Talk' for the 2011\u20132012 season|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/01/26/cbs-renews-the-talk-for-the-2011-2012-season/80332|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> a 25% decrease from ''[[As the World Turns]]''{{'}}s ratings the previous year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Scott|title=CBS makes lower ratings roll the right way for Julie Chen and 'The Talk'|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/01/cbs-finds-a-way-to-make-low-ratings-roll-the-right-way-for-julie-chens-the-talk-.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]]|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBy June 2012, ''The Talk'' averaged 1.7/6 in households, 2.29 million viewers, 1.1/7 in women 25\u201354 and 0.8/5 in women 18\u201349. The women 25\u201354 rating was ''The Talk''{{'}}s highest since the week ending February 17, while the women 18\u201349 rating was the best since the week ending May 4. Compared to the same week last year, ''The Talk'' was up +21% in households (from 1.4/4), +24% in viewers (from. 1.85m), +38% in women 25\u201354 (from 0.8/5) and +33% in women 18\u201349 (from 0.6/4).<ref>{{cite web|last=Bibel|first=Sara|title=The Talk' Delivers Its Highest Rating Since February|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/06/14/the-talk-delivers-its-highest-women-25-54-rating-since-february/138168/|accessdate=June 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\n''The Talk'' was criticized for a segment where some panelists made light of male genital mutilation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hughes|first=Sarah|title=\u2018The Talk\u2019 ladies under fire for laughing at Catherine Kieu story (Video)|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/celebritology/post/the-talk-ladies-under-fire-for-laughing-at-catherine-kieu-story-video/2011/07/18/gIQA3OjkLI_blog.html|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[Adams Publishing Group]]|accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref> Osbourne said, \"However, I do think it is quite fabulous\" in response to a story where a wife had drugged her husband, cut off his penis, and put it in the garbage disposal due to his filing for divorce. An apology was made during a subsequent show.\n\nThe failure to disclose on-air as to why Remini and Robinson Peete were released or even mention them brought about criticism of the show from some viewers, with some fans of the two stars protesting their dismissals.<ref>{{cite news|title='The Talk' Debuts Without Leah Remini and Holly Robinson Peete: What the Viewers Are Saying|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/talk-debuts-leah-remini-holly-231686|author=Jethro Nede|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=September 6, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='The Talk' Without Leah Remini and Holly Robinson Peete: What THR Readers Are Saying |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/talk-leah-remini-holly-robinson-232147|author=Jethro Nede|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=September 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Recipients\n! Result\n|-\n! 2012\n| rowspan=8|[[Daytime Emmy Awards]]\n| rowspan=3|[[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Entertainment#Winners and nominees|Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! 2013 \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2014 \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host#Winners and nominees|Outstanding Talk Show Host(s)]]\n| Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2015\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! rowspan=3|2016\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| rowspan=2|Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[People's Choice Awards]]\n| [[42nd People's Choice Awards#Television|Favorite Daytime TV Hosting Team]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2017\n| rowspan=6|[[Daytime Emmy Awards]]\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2018\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2019\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| Chen, [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]], Gilbert, [[Carrie Ann Inaba]], Osbourne, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==International broadcasts==\n* In Australia, ''The Talk'' began broadcasting on August 6, 2012 on [[Network Ten]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/07/axed-the-circle.html|title=Axed: The Circle|first=David|last=Knox|publisher=TV tonight|date=July 30, 2012|accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> as a replacement for controversially axed local talk show ''[[The Circle (TV program)|The Circle]]''. ''The Talk'' rates lower than the former local offering, achieving just 29,000 viewers on August 15<ref name=\"Aug15ratings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/08/puberty-blues-hits-sweet-spot-for-ten.html|title=Puberty Blues hits sweet spot for TEN|first=David|last=Knox|publisher=TV tonight|date=August 16, 2012|accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> compared to the axed show's 39,000 two months earlier,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/06/3-1m-as-karise-is-announced-as-the-voice.html|title=3.1m as Karise is announced as The Voice|first=David|last=Knox|publisher=TV tonight|date=June 19, 2012|accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> and well below rival programs [[Seven Network|Channel Seven]]'s ''[[The Morning Show (TV program)|The Morning Show]]'' and [[Nine Network|Channel Nine]]'s ''[[Mornings (TV program)|Mornings]]'' which rated 200,000 and 119,000 viewers respectively.<ref name=\"Aug15ratings\" />\n* In Canada, ''The Talk'' airs simultaneously on the [[Global Television Network]] and on [[CJON-TV|NTV]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]].\n* In the [[United Kingdom]], ''The Talk'' began been broadcasting on July 4, 2011 on [[Diva TV]].\n* In South Africa, ''The Talk'' began broadcasting on April 1, 2011 in the 1&nbsp;pm timeslot on [[MNet]].\n* In the Philippines, the program was formerly aired on [[Solar News Channel]], but they discontinued airing in September 2013 after season 4 is aired. Season 5 is aired of March 2015 on [[CT (TV channel)|CT]].\n* In the [[Czech Republic]], ''The Talk'' airs on Prima Love.\n* In [[New Zealand]], ''The Talk'' began broadcasting on January 23, 2012 on TV3.\n* In the [[Arab world]], ''The Talk'' airs on [[MBC 4 (Middle East)|MBC 4]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cbs.com/shows/the_talk/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1740718|The Talk}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-talk|The Talk}}\n\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Talk Show Entertainment}}\n{{U.S. daytime talk shows}}\n{{CBSNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Talk (Tv Series), The}}\n[[Category:2010 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:2020s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:CBS original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Talk\n| image                    = The Talk logo.png\n| genre                    = [[Talk show]]\n| creator                  = [[Sara Gilbert]]\n| director                 = \n| presenter                = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Julie Chen]]\n* Sara Gilbert\n* [[Sharon Osbourne]]\n* [[Marissa Jaret Winokur]]\n* [[Leah Remini]]\n* [[Holly Robinson Peete]]\n* [[Aisha Tyler]]\n* [[Sheryl Underwood]]\n* [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]]\n* [[Carrie Ann Inaba]]\n* [[Marie Osmond]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Gregg Wattenberg]]\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 10\n| num_episodes             = 2,033 (as of January 10, 2020)<ref>{{cite web|title=''The Talk'' Episodes on CBS|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-talk/episodes-season-4/307541|work=TV Guide|accessdate=February 15, 2014}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2019}}\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = Sara Gilbert<br>Brad Bessey (2010\u201311)<br>Susan Winston (2011)<ref>{{cite web|title=Susan Winston Joins CBS' 'The Talk'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/susan-winston-joins-cbs-talk-181552|author=Lesley Goldberg|periodical=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Guggenheim Partners|Prometheus Global Media]]|date=April 22, 2011|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref><br>John Redmann (2010\u2013)<ref>{{cite web|title=New Exec Producer of CBS' 'The Talk' Out After Two Weeks|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/susan-winston-as-talk-exec-192902|author=Sofia M. Fernandez|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=May 28, 2011|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n| producer                 = \n| location                 = {{unbulleted list|[[CBS Studio Center]]|[[Studio City, California]]}}\n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 42 minutes\n| company                  = [[CBS Television Studios]]\n| distributor              = \n| network                  = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[high-definition television|HDTV]])\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2010|10|18}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| related                  = ''[[Loose Women]]''\n| website                  = http://www.cbs.com/shows/the_talk/\n| production_website       = \n}}\n\n'''''The Talk''''' is an<!--Do not add things like \"Emmy-Award winning\" or \"People's Choice Award winning,\" that is undue weight.--> [[United States|American]] [[talk show]] that debuted on October 18, 2010, as part of [[CBS]]'s [[CBS Daytime|daytime]] programming block.<ref name=\"cbs_order\">{{cite web|title=CBS Orders New Daytime Talk Show for Fall |url= http://www.cbspressexpress.com/div.php/cbs_entertainment/release?id=25604|website=CBS PressExpress|publisher=[[CBS]]|date=July 22, 2010|accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> The show was developed by actress and host [[Sara Gilbert]].\n\nThe show features [[Sharon Osbourne]], [[Sheryl Underwood]], [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]], [[Carrie Ann Inaba]] (who also serves as the show's moderator) and [[Marie Osmond]]. They discuss the day's latest headlines, while usually tying in the show's theme of motherhood or at least parenthood, such as by giving their opinions \"through the eyes of mothers.\" The show also contains celebrity interviews and segments for mothers and parents in general.\n\n''The Talk'' is broadcast before a live studio audience at the [[CBS Studio Center]] in [[Studio City, California]] each Monday through Friday at 11:00 a.m. [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific Time]], and airs live on most CBS [[owned-and-operated station]]s and [[network affiliate|affiliates]] in the [[Eastern United States|Eastern]] and [[Central United States]] at 2:00 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]]. The program is broadcast on [[broadcast delay|tape delay]] elsewhere from the [[Mountain Time Zone]] westward. The Friday shows are recorded on Thursday afternoons at 1:00&nbsp;pm PT for broadcast the next day. Friday shows are taped before the same studio audience in attendance for the earlier live Thursday broadcast.\n\n==Format==\n''The Talk'' has a format similar in style to [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]''.  The opening segment of the broadcast is known as \"Everybody Talks\" and usually runs a combined 12 to 25 minutes over multiple segments, depending on the number of stories featured and the number of guests.  It is followed by topical discussion segments, involves the five-female host panel discussing current news items, typically focusing on [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] headlines, offbeat stories, and celebrity news. The program also actively incorporates [[social media]] to allow viewers to provide their opinions on the stories discussed through [[Twitter]] (using the hashtag #EverybodyTalks, or alternately the abbreviated #EVBT).  In season five, the program began allowing viewers to use [[Instagram]] to record and upload videos using the aforementioned hashtags, with one or two videos being selected to air on the live broadcasts.<ref>{{cite press release|title=CBS's \"The Talk\" Kicks Off Season 5 Monday, Sept. 8!|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2014/09/02/cbss-the-talk-kicks-off-season-5-monday-sept-8-45010/20140902cbs01/|publisher=CBS|via=The Futon Critic|date=September 2, 2014|accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn most editions, the \"Top Talker\" serves as the final segment of the topical discussion, featuring a rotating set of contributors - most of whom are correspondents/hosts of entertainment-related newsmagazine programs or magazines or hosts of local or syndicated radio programs - providing detailed analysis of a single trending, usually celebrity-related, story. Following the \"Everybody Talks\" segment, all five hosts interview one or two featured celebrity guests; most of these interviews are conducted at the set's roundtable. Musical performances are also occasionally included.\n\nThe show also regularly has a cooking segment two to four times each week, with two of the panelists - rotating between any combination of Chen, Underwood, Gilbert, or Osbourne - assisting in the preparation of the featured recipes with the guest chef. Product giveaways are also done once per week, as part of a segment showcasing fashion/beauty products and electronics that are given away to studio audience members for attending the show, and are often tied into online [[Deal of the day|flash sale]]s where the viewing audience can purchase the products offered at a reduced price.\n\nTo conclude the show through season 9, each episode signed-off with one of the co-hosts, primarily the moderator, saying \"Remember, it's always the right time to have ''The Talk!''\". With the start of season 10 the sign-off \"Let's Talk Tomorrow!\" or \"Let's Talk Later\" (used on Friday) is used.\n\n==Development==\nIn December 2009, CBS announced the cancellation of ''[[As the World Turns]]'' after 54 years, and was looking for a program to replace the long-running [[soap opera]] in its time slot. Sara Gilbert approached CBS about producing a pilot that would feature six women talking about the day's headlines with opinions told through \"the eyes of mothers.\"<ref name = Mothers />\n\nOn July 21, 2010, CBS announced that it had picked up the show (by then, given the title ''The Talk''), beating out several other contenders, including a cooking show featuring [[Emeril Lagasse]]; ''Say It Now'', a talk show featuring [[Valerie Bertinelli]] and [[Rove McManus]]; and a revamped version of the classic game show ''[[Pyramid (game show)|Pyramid]]'', hosted by [[Andy Richter]].<ref name=Mothers>{{cite web|title=Sara Gilbert talk show to replace veteran CBS soap|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/07/21/us-gilbert-idUSTRE66K5XA20100721|author=Georg Szalai|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=September 19, 2012|date=July 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the 4 weeks prior to the show's debut, new episodes of ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]'' and ''[[Let's Make a Deal]]'', as well as repeats of ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'', aired in the timeslot vacated by ''As the World Turns''.\n\n==Co-hosts==\n\n=== Timeline ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width:\"100%\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Co-host !!  colspan=10 style=text-align:center; | Seasons\n|-\n!! width=\"80\" | 1 !! width=\"80\" | 2 !! width=\"80\" | 3 !! width=\"80\" | 4 !! width=\"80\" | 5 !! width=\"80\"| 6 !! width=\"80\" | 7 !! width=\"80\" |8 !! width=\"80\" | 9 !! width=\"80\" | 10\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Julie Chen]]}} || colspan=\"8\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Sara Gilbert]]}} || colspan=\"9\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Sharon Osbourne]]}} || colspan=\"10\" {{yes|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Marissa Jaret Winokur]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"9\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Holly Robinson Peete]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"9\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Leah Remini]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"9\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Aisha Tyler]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"6\" {{yes|}} || colspan=\"3\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Sheryl Underwood]]}} || colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"9\" {{yes|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Eve (rapper)|Eve]]}} || colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"3\" {{yes|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Carrie Ann Inaba]]}} || colspan=\"8\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"2\" {{yes|}}\n|-\n| {{nowrap|[[Marie Osmond]]}} || colspan=\"9\" {{n/a|}} || colspan=\"1\" {{yes|}}\n|}\n\n===Season 1===\nThe original panel consisted of [[Sara Gilbert]], known for her role on the TV series ''[[Roseanne]]''; [[Holly Robinson Peete]], known for her roles on the TV series ''[[21 Jump Street]]'' and ''[[Hangin' with Mr. Cooper]]''; [[Leah Remini]], known for her role as Carrie Heffernan in the 1998\u20132007 CBS sitcom ''[[The King of Queens]]''; ''[[Big Brother (U.S.)|Big Brother]]'' hostess [[Julie Chen]]; and former talk show hostess/''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|X Factor]]'' judge [[Sharon Osbourne]], the wife of rocker [[Ozzy Osbourne]]. [[Marissa Jaret Winokur]] was featured in an out-of-the studio position as the \"mother on the street,\" dealing with issues like taking her toddler on an airplane, talking with kids about sex, talking to parents about the \"[[Child development stage|terrible twos]]\" and other parental issues.\n\nOn January 14, 2011, Marissa Jaret Winokur reported that she would not be returning to the show in 2011. In an exclusive statement to ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', original executive producer Brad Bessey said of Winokur's departure, \"We think the world of Marissa as a creative talent, on-air personality and super mom. This is a mutual decision based on time, not talent.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Hairspray's Marissa Jaret Winokur Exits CBS' \"The Talk\"|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/146759-Hairsprays-Marissa-Jaret-Winokur-Exits-CBS-The-Talk|author=Adam Hetrick|periodical=[[Playbill]]|publisher=Philip S Birsh (Rights and Permissions)|date=January 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Marissa Jaret Winokur Leaves 'The Talk'|url=http://www.popeater.com/2011/01/15/marissa-jaret-winokur-leaves-the-talk/|author=Christine Fenno|website=PopEater|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]] ([[AOL]])|date=January 15, 2011|accessdate= April 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhen ''[[America's Got Talent]]'' resumed filming on March 2, 2011, Osbourne's daughter [[Kelly Osbourne]] began filling in for her on a substitute basis, as the show's first substitute host.\n\nOn August 26, 2011, it was announced that original co-host Leah Remini had been released from the show.<ref>{{cite web|title=It's Official: Leah Remini Is Leaving The Talk|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/moviestvmusic/news/its-official-leah-remini-is-leaving-the-talk-2011268|periodical=[[Us Magazine]]|publisher=[[Wenner Media]]|date=August 26, 2011|accessdate=December 26, 2011}}</ref> On September 2, 2011, it was confirmed that Holly Robinson Peete had also been released from the show.<ref>{{cite web|title=Enough Talk: Holly Robinson Peete \"Officially\" Not Returning to Chatfest|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/261761/enough-talk-holly-robinson-peete-officially-not-returning-to-chatfest|author=Brandi Fowler|website=[[E!|E! Online]]|publisher=[[Comcast|Comcast Entertainment Group]]|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=December 26, 2011}}</ref> Sharon Osbourne eventually gave opinion on their dismissals in December 2011 on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', stating: \"Some people don't really know who they are, and you have to know who you are when you're in something like this. You can't pretend to be something you're not. You have to know your brand. You can't be all things to everyone.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Howard Stern Gets The Talk Hosts To Finally Talk About Holly Robinson Peete Leah Remini Diss|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/howard_stern_gets_talk_hosts_finally/280413#ixzz1lrlsRcpC|website=E! Online|publisher=Comcast Entertainment Group|date=December 13, 2011|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sharon Osbourne, Leah Remini in Twitter feud about 'King of Queens' actress' dismissal from 'The Talk'?|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/television/sharon-osbourne-leah-remini-twitter-feud-king-queens-actress-dismissal-talk-article-1.1040078?localLinksEnabled=false|author=Joyce Chen|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman|Daily News, L.P.]]|date=March 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Seasons 2\u20135===\nOn August 26, 2011, CBS announced that comedian [[Sheryl Underwood]] would join the panel as a co-host at the start of its second season; Underwood was officially added to the program on September 6, 2011, beginning with that season's premiere episode.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kris Jenner to guest co-host 'The Talk'|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2011/08/kris-jenner-to-guest-co-host-the-talk-/1|author=Ann Oldenburg|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Molly Shannon]] served as the (guest) co-host during the month of September 2011. Actress and comedian [[Aisha Tyler]]'s addition to the panel was announced on October 23, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aisha Tyler to Co-Host CBS' 'The Talk'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/aisha-tyler-the-talk-host-252298 |author=Kimberly Nordyke|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=October 23, 2011|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Season 6===\nOn October 12, 2016, the episode of ''The Talk'' aired special tributes to four CBS [[soap opera]]s such as ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' (March 26, 1973\u2013present), ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]'' (March 23, 1987\u2013present), ''[[As the World Turns]]'' (April 2, 1956 \u2013 September 17, 2010), and ''[[Guiding Light]]'' (June 30, 1952 \u2013 September 18, 2009).\n\n===Season 7\u20138===\nOn June 15, 2017, Aisha Tyler announced she would leave the series following the completion of the series' seventh season. She said she would return as a guest host and to promote her various projects. Her last show aired on August 4, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/06/15/aisha-tyler-leaving-talk/|title=Aisha Tyler Chokes Back Tears Announcing Her Exit From CBS' 'The Talk'|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/aisha-tyler-leaving-cbs-talk-1013879|title=Aisha Tyler Leaving CBS' 'The Talk'|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Swift|first1=Andy|title=Aisha Tyler Leaving CBS' ''The Talk'' \u2014 Watch Her Emotional Announcement|url=http://tvline.com/2017/06/15/aisha-tyler-leaving-the-talk-cbs-announcement/|website=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=June 15, 2017|location=United States|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref> The current hosts of ''The Talk'' auditioned ladies on air as \"dates\" to fill in Aisha's seat. At the start of the eighth season, some of the guest hosts included [[Carrie Ann Inaba]], [[Garcelle Beauvais]], [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]], [[Sasheer Zamata]] and [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]]. Eve was announced as the fifth permanent co-host on November 14, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/the-talk-eve-cohost-cbs-show-season-8-aisha-tyler-1202613967/|title=\u2018The Talk\u2019 Adds Eve as Permanent Co-Host Following Aisha Tyler Departure|website=Variety|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Season 9===\nIn a promo for the ninth season, it was revealed that all five co-hosts would return to the panel. However, Chen did not return to the show for the ninth season premiere amid sexual misconduct allegations against her husband [[Leslie Moonves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/julie-chen-leslie-moonves-the-talk-cbs-1202934476/|title=Julie Chen Absent From \u2018The Talk\u2019 Season 9 Premiere Amid Moonves Ouster|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Rebecca|last=Rubin|date=September 10, 2018|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref> Chen officially announced her departure from the talk show in a pre-taped message on Tuesday, September 18, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Iannucci |first1=Rebecca |last2=Swift |first2=Andy |title=''The Talk''{{'}}s Julie Chen Confirms Exit in Tearful Video Message: 'I Will Always Cherish the Memories' \u2014 Watch |url=https://tvline.com/2018/09/18/julie-chen-leaving-the-talk-watch-video-message-final-episode/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=September 18, 2018 |location=United States |date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/julie-chen-the-talk-exit-1202946749/|title=Julie Chen Officially Exits \u2018The Talk\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Rebecca|last=Rubin|date=September 18, 2018|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> On December 6, 2018, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' announced that Inaba had been chosen to join the show as a permanent co-host, with a projected January 2019 debut.<ref>{{cite news |last=Otterson |first=Joe |title=Carrie Ann Inaba to Permanently Replace Julie Chen on ''The Talk'' (EXCLUSIVE) |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/the-talk-carrie-ann-inaba-julie-chen-1203081973/ |accessdate=December 7, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=December 6, 2018 |location=United States |language=en}}</ref> Inaba officially joined the show on January 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last=de Moraes|first=Lisa|title=CBS Makes It Official: Carrie Ann Inaba Debuts as Julie Chen Replacement on ''The Talk''|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/carrie-ann-inaba-official-debut-julie-chen-replacement-the-talk-1202527925/|accessdate=January 2, 2019|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the April 9, 2019, episode, Gilbert announced she would depart the talk show at the conclusion of its ninth season; she cited acting opportunities and her desire to produce other projects as the reason for her departure;<ref>{{cite web |last=Iannucci |first=Rebecca |title=Sara Gilbert Leaving ''The Talk'' |url=https://tvline.com/2019/04/09/sara-gilbert-leaving-the-talk-video/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=April 9, 2019 |location=United States |date=April 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Harnick |first=Chris |title=Sara Gilbert Leaving ''The Talk'' After Nine Seasons |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1031071/sara-gilbert-leaving-the-talk-after-nine-seasons |website=[[E! Online]] |publisher=[[NBCUniversal]] |accessdate=April 9, 2019 |location=United States |date=April 9, 2019}}</ref> her final episode aired on August 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last=Swift |first=Andy |title=Sara Gilbert's Last Day on ''The Talk'': Watch Her Emotional Goodbye |url=https://tvline.com/2019/08/02/the-talk-sara-gilbert-leaves-watch-video-last-episode/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |location=United States |language=en |date=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Season 10===\nThe tenth season premiered on September 9, 2019, with [[Marie Osmond]] replacing Gilbert as co-host.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rice |first=Lynette |title=''The Talk'' recruits Marie Osmond to replace Sara Gilbert |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/05/07/the-talk-marie-osmond-replacing-sara-gilbert/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |location=United States |date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Yang |first=Rachel |title=''The Talk'' Sets Marie Osmond to Replace Sara Gilbert as Host |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/the-talk-sets-marie-osmond-replace-sara-gilbert-host-1203207739/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=May 7, 2019 |location=United States |date=May 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to Osmond's addition, a brand-new, state-of-the-art set was unveiled.<ref>{{cite web |last=Webb Mitovich |first=Matt |title=''The Talk'' Video Teases 'Two New Faces' \u2014 Including Sharon's Latest Facelift! |url=https://tvline.com/2019/09/05/the-talk-season-10-video-sharon-osbourne-facelift-marie-osmond-host/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=September 9, 2019 |location=United States |language=en |date=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable events==\n{{cleanup section|reason=some events are not notable|date=May 2017}}\n\n===Season premieres===\nThe first week of shows featured several celebrity guests, including model [[Christie Brinkley]], singer/actress [[Jennifer Lopez]], actress/director [[Chandra Wilson]], actress/author [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], and former South Carolina first lady [[Jenny Sanford]].<ref name=\"fancast_firstweekguests\">{{cite web|title=CBS\u2019 \u2018The Talk\u2019 Unveils First Week of High-Profile Guests|url=http://www.fancast.com/blogs/2010/tv-news/cbs-the-talk-unveils-first-week-of-high-profile-guests/|author=Tracy Phillips|website=Fancast|publisher=Comcast Interactive Media, LLC.|accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe third-season premiere (aired on September 10, 2012) featured all five co-hosts, as well as members of the studio audience, without their make-up and dressed in robes during the broadcast; all of the co-hosts were also shown beside pictures of themselves with make-up. The guests for that edition, who also participated in the stunt, were [[Jamie Lee Curtis]]; [[Michelle Stafford]] and [[Melody Thomas Scott]] of ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''; and [[Katherine Kelly Lang]] of ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Women of The Talk Go Makeup-Free|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/the-talk-hosts-no-makeup-1052851/|author=Sadie Gennis|website=[[TV Guide]]|publisher=Open Gate Capital|date=September 11, 2012|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Women of 'The Talk' go makeup-free -- VIDEO|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2012/09/10/women-of-the-talk-go-makeup-free-video|author=Lynette Rice|periodical=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=September 10, 2012|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe premiere weeks of the fourth and fifth seasons (September 9 to 13, 2013 and September 8 to 12, 2014) featured \"''The Talk'' Tells All\", a daily feature on the season's first week of shows in which co-hosts Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler and Underwood revealed never-before-disclosed personal secrets on-air.<ref>{{cite press release|title='The Talk' Announces Season 4 Premiere Week Line-Up|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/09/05/the-talk-announces-season-4-premiere-week-line-up/201158/|author=Sara Bibel|website=TV by the Numbers|date=September 5, 2013|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeason six premiered on September 14, 2015 with a slightly new set design featuring three new large monitors with backdrops including palm trees and the [[Los Angeles]] skyline. Season seven premiered on September 12, 2016, with the same set. The hosts kicked off premiere week by unveiling answers to the viewers' biggest questions with a theme they called \"''The 7 Wonders of The Talk''.\" <ref>{{cite web|title=The Talk's Seventh Season Promises Laughter, Friendship, And Wonder|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/the_talk/news/1005783/the-talk-s-seventh-season-promises-laughter-friendship-and-wonder/|website=cbs.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===On-location editions===\nThe show made two trips to New York City during its second season, broadcasting live for one week on each trip. The first trip placed some audience members inside and some outside the studio.<ref>{{cite press release|title=\nCBS\u2019s \"The Talk\" Heads To New York City For A Week Of Shows To Air Dec. 12-16|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/12/08/cbs%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%9Cthe-talk%E2%80%9D-heads-to-new-york-city-for-a-week-of-shows-to-air-dec-12-16/113149/|website=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=December 8, 2011|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref> Beginning with the second trip, the show began to tape its New York City-based episodes in a studio at the [[CBS Broadcast Center]], similar in structure to its Los Angeles studio, with the audience members based within the soundstage. ''The Talk'' has done week-long broadcasts from New York City twice per season since then (usually during the February and May [[sweeps]] periods and in December), with the Thursday and Friday episodes being recorded on the same day as the Tuesday and Wednesday live broadcasts.<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS' 'The Talk' will move to New York for a week in May and compete with Barbara Walters' 'The View'|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/confidential/cbs-talk-moves-nyc-week-article-1.1316495|newspaper=New York Daily News|publisher=Daily News, L.P.|date=April 14, 2013|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref> The program's first set of New York City episodes in the third season (from December 10 to 14, 2012), featured a partnership with [[Toys for Tots]], asking all guests and audience members to bring a new unwrapped toy to donate to the charity.\n\nDuring the third season, ''The Talk'' broadcast a week of episodes from [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]] \u2013 site of [[Super Bowl XLVII]] - from January 28, 2013 to February 1, 2013, to help promote CBS's coverage of the [[National Football League]] championship game.\n\n===''The Talk After Dark''===\nFrom January 12 to 16, 2015, CBS broadcast a special second \"[[late night television|late night]]\" edition of ''The Talk'' \u2013 unofficially titled ''The Talk After Dark'' - which filled the 12:37&nbsp;a.m. Eastern timeslot normally occupied by ''[[The Late Late Show (CBS TV series)|The Late Late Show]]'' (which itself utilized [[List of The Late Late Show episodes (2015 guest hosts)|guest hosts]] on most other weeks in the four-month period between [[Craig Ferguson]]'s departure from ''The Late Late Show'' in December 2014 and the start of [[James Corden]]'s tenure as host of that program in March 2015). Recorded each afternoon that week before the studio audience in attendance for the earlier live daytime broadcasts for broadcast each night, the episodes featured a separate slate of guests and featured topics from the daytime editions, and featured a special [[house band]] exclusive to the late-night editions led by rock musician/songwriter [[Linda Perry]] (wife of series creator and co-host Sara Gilbert).<ref>{{cite web|title=CBS Taps \u2018The Talk\u2019 and Guest Hosts To Fill \u2018Late Late Show\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/cbs-taps-the-talk-and-guest-hosts-to-fill-late-late-show-1201365480/|author=Brian Steinberg|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=November 26, 2014|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Breaking News - Guests Announced for \"The Late Late Show\" with Guest Host Drew Carey (1/5-1/9) and After-Dark Edition of \"The Talk\" (1/12-1/16)|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2014/12/22/guests-announced-for-the-late-late-show-with-guest-host-drew-carey-1-5-1-9-and-after-dark-edition-of-the-talk-1-12-1-16-742210/20141222cbs01/|website=The Futon Critic|date=December 22, 2014|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===''The Talk: Keep Talking''===\nFrom March 15 to 16, 2018 ''The Talk'' aired two exclusive episodes on their Facebook page entitled ''Keep Talking'' as CBS broadcast the [[NCAA March Madness]] games on the aforementioned dates. This special edition featured all five co-hosts communicating with their Facebook fans asking them personal questions and advice for their own personal problems. Unlike a normal episode the topics are decided entirely by the fans. Both episodes are similar to ''[[The Real (talk show)|The Real]]'s'' online exclusive segments and both episodes are around four minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=You're Invited To \"Keep Talking!\"\n|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheTalkCBS/videos/1653734334663498/|website=Facebook|date=March 9, 2018|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Keep Talking: The Hosts' Pre-Show Rituals|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheTalkCBS/videos/1659254500778148/|website=Facebook|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Keep Talking: Dating Advice|url=https://www.facebook.com/TheTalkCBS/videos/1659260670777531/|website=Facebook|date=March 16, 2018|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===''The Talk: Chat Room''===\nCarrie Ann Inaba originally announced on the March 12, 2020 episode that due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] The Talk will be shot without an audience. After CBS forced production to shut down Inaba took matters into her own hands by hosting a daily Instagram live from her own house (at the same time when the show originally airs) under self quarantine. CBS greenlit Inaba's daily [[Instagram]] live (now including all five co-hosts) into ''The Talk: Chat Room'' as production was shut down. Guests on this version included [[Raven Symone]], [[Dr. Phil]], [[Olivia Newton-John]], [[The Bella Twins]] and [[Tyra Banks]].\n\n===''The Talk: @Home''===\nStarting March 30, 2020 the show will now be shot from each co-hosts (and guests) home via [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] also due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]]. [[Wayne Brady]] will be their first guest. Other guests will include [[Jaime Camil]], [[Pauley Perrette]], [[Dr. Oz]], [[Terry Crews]], [[Sean Hayes]] and [[Sebastian Maniscalco]].\n\n==Appearances in other media==\nOn March 14, 2016, all of ''The Talk'' hosts (including then host [[Aisha Tyler]]) made a cameo on ''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]'' in the episode \"Falling\" when [[Cat Grant]] (played by [[Calista Flockhart]]) made a guest appearance on ''The Talk''. On December 15, 2017, [[Julie Chen]] revealed that all of the current hosts of The Talk (including new co-host [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]]) will be featured on an episode of [[Jane the Virgin]] as themselves which was directed by [[Gina Rodriguez]]. On January 10, 2018, ''The Talk'' revealed on their Instagram and Snapchat stories they filmed their episode of ''Jane the Virgin'' on the set of ''The Talk'' right after filming the show for the aforementioned date. On February 9, 2018, Rodriguez made a guest appearance on the show to announce the episode featuring the ladies of ''The Talk'', called \"Chapter Seventy-Four\" would air that night.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Ratings===\nThe debut episode of ''The Talk'' was number one in its timeslot in 20 of the 56 markets.<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite web|last=Seidman|first=Robert|title=Premiere of CBS's 'The Talk' 24% Better than October 2009 Avg for 'As the World Turns'|url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2010/10/19/premiere-of-cbss-the-talk-24-better-than-october-2009-avg-for-as-the-world-turns/68697|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> As of October 2011, ''The Talk'' averaged 1.83 million viewers per episode,<ref>{{cite web|last=Seidman|first=Robert|title=CBS Renews 'The Talk' for the 2011\u20132012 season|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/01/26/cbs-renews-the-talk-for-the-2011-2012-season/80332|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> a 25% decrease from ''[[As the World Turns]]''{{'}}s ratings the previous year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Scott|title=CBS makes lower ratings roll the right way for Julie Chen and 'The Talk'|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/01/cbs-finds-a-way-to-make-low-ratings-roll-the-right-way-for-julie-chens-the-talk-.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]]|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBy June 2012, ''The Talk'' averaged 1.7/6 in households, 2.29 million viewers, 1.1/7 in women 25\u201354 and 0.8/5 in women 18\u201349. The women 25\u201354 rating was ''The Talk''{{'}}s highest since the week ending February 17, while the women 18\u201349 rating was the best since the week ending May 4. Compared to the same week last year, ''The Talk'' was up +21% in households (from 1.4/4), +24% in viewers (from. 1.85m), +38% in women 25\u201354 (from 0.8/5) and +33% in women 18\u201349 (from 0.6/4).<ref>{{cite web|last=Bibel|first=Sara|title=The Talk' Delivers Its Highest Rating Since February|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/06/14/the-talk-delivers-its-highest-women-25-54-rating-since-february/138168/|accessdate=June 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\n''The Talk'' was criticized for a segment where some panelists made light of male genital mutilation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hughes|first=Sarah|title=\u2018The Talk\u2019 ladies under fire for laughing at Catherine Kieu story (Video)|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/celebritology/post/the-talk-ladies-under-fire-for-laughing-at-catherine-kieu-story-video/2011/07/18/gIQA3OjkLI_blog.html|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[Adams Publishing Group]]|accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref> Osbourne said, \"However, I do think it is quite fabulous\" in response to a story where a wife had drugged her husband, cut off his penis, and put it in the garbage disposal due to his filing for divorce. An apology was made during a subsequent show.\n\nThe failure to disclose on-air as to why Remini and Robinson Peete were released or even mention them brought about criticism of the show from some viewers, with some fans of the two stars protesting their dismissals.<ref>{{cite news|title='The Talk' Debuts Without Leah Remini and Holly Robinson Peete: What the Viewers Are Saying|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/talk-debuts-leah-remini-holly-231686|author=Jethro Nede|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=September 6, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='The Talk' Without Leah Remini and Holly Robinson Peete: What THR Readers Are Saying |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/talk-leah-remini-holly-robinson-232147|author=Jethro Nede|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=September 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Recipients\n! Result\n|-\n! 2012\n| rowspan=8|[[Daytime Emmy Awards]]\n| rowspan=3|[[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Entertainment#Winners and nominees|Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! 2013 \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2014 \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host#Winners and nominees|Outstanding Talk Show Host(s)]]\n| Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2015\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! rowspan=3|2016\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| rowspan=2|Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[People's Choice Awards]]\n| [[42nd People's Choice Awards#Television|Favorite Daytime TV Hosting Team]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2017\n| rowspan=6|[[Daytime Emmy Awards]]\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2018\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| Chen, Gilbert, Osbourne, Tyler, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|2019\n| Outstanding Talk Show/Entertainment \n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Entertainment Talk Show Host\n| Chen, [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]], Gilbert, [[Carrie Ann Inaba]], Osbourne, Underwood\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==International broadcasts==\n* In Australia, ''The Talk'' began broadcasting on August 6, 2012 on [[Network Ten]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/07/axed-the-circle.html|title=Axed: The Circle|first=David|last=Knox|publisher=TV tonight|date=July 30, 2012|accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> as a replacement for controversially axed local talk show ''[[The Circle (TV program)|The Circle]]''. ''The Talk'' rates lower than the former local offering, achieving just 29,000 viewers on August 15<ref name=\"Aug15ratings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/08/puberty-blues-hits-sweet-spot-for-ten.html|title=Puberty Blues hits sweet spot for TEN|first=David|last=Knox|publisher=TV tonight|date=August 16, 2012|accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> compared to the axed show's 39,000 two months earlier,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/06/3-1m-as-karise-is-announced-as-the-voice.html|title=3.1m as Karise is announced as The Voice|first=David|last=Knox|publisher=TV tonight|date=June 19, 2012|accessdate=August 16, 2012}}</ref> and well below rival programs [[Seven Network|Channel Seven]]'s ''[[The Morning Show (TV program)|The Morning Show]]'' and [[Nine Network|Channel Nine]]'s ''[[Mornings (TV program)|Mornings]]'' which rated 200,000 and 119,000 viewers respectively.<ref name=\"Aug15ratings\" />\n* In Canada, ''The Talk'' airs simultaneously on the [[Global Television Network]] and on [[CJON-TV|NTV]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador]].\n* In the [[United Kingdom]], ''The Talk'' began been broadcasting on July 4, 2011 on [[Diva TV]].\n* In South Africa, ''The Talk'' began broadcasting on April 1, 2011 in the 1&nbsp;pm timeslot on [[MNet]].\n* In the Philippines, the program was formerly aired on [[Solar News Channel]], but they discontinued airing in September 2013 after season 4 is aired. Season 5 is aired of March 2015 on [[CT (TV channel)|CT]].\n* In the [[Czech Republic]], ''The Talk'' airs on Prima Love.\n* In [[New Zealand]], ''The Talk'' began broadcasting on January 23, 2012 on TV3.\n* In the [[Arab world]], ''The Talk'' airs on [[MBC 4 (Middle East)|MBC 4]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cbs.com/shows/the_talk/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1740718|The Talk}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-talk|The Talk}}\n\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Talk Show Entertainment}}\n{{U.S. daytime talk shows}}\n{{CBSNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Talk (Tv Series), The}}\n[[Category:2010 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:2020s American television talk shows]]\n[[Category:CBS original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Bucsfannva", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason 10:Added info for The Talk@Home", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Talk_(talk_show)"}
{"title_page": "Benedict Brogan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               =  Benedict Brogan\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              =  <!-- filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" (or \"Image:\") prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  <!-- {{birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         =  <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| education          = [[Lyc\u00e9e Rochambeau]], [[Bethesda, Maryland]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]<br/>\n[[University of Cambridge]]\n| occupation         = Journalist, columnist, public relations officer\n| employer           = [[Lloyds Banking Group]]\n| title              = Deputy Editor, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<ref name=\"Sommers\"/>\n| term               = 2009-2014\n| predecessor        = [[Tony Gallagher]]\n| successor          = [[Allister Heath]]\n| boards             = Director [[public relations|public affairs]], [[Lloyds Banking Group]]\n| spouse             = [[Melanie Dawes]]\n| children           = One daughter\n| website            =[http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/author/benedictbrogan Brogan blogsite]\n}}\n\n'''Benedict \"Ben\" Brogan''' is a British journalist, formerly deputy editor and chief political commentator of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.<ref name=\"Sommers\">Jack Sommers [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/06/18/telegraph-cuts-highprofile-journalists_n_5506465.html \"Telegraph Cuts High-Profile Journalists Benedict Brogan and Damian Thompson in Latest Cull\"], ''The Huffington Post'', 18 June 2014</ref> In December 2014, six months after resigning his posts at ''The Telegraph'',<ref name=\"Sommers\"/> Brogan was appointed group director of [[public relations|public affairs]] at [[Lloyds Banking Group]].<ref name=PRWk1324440>[http://www.prweek.com/article/1324440/lloyds-appoints-telegraph-deputy-editor-benedict-brogan-public-affairs-director \"Lloyds appoints 'Telegraph' deputy editor Benedict Brogan as public affairs director\"], prweek.com, 1 December 2014; accessed 2 May 2015.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBrogan was born to an English father and a French mother, and was brought up in [[Washington, D.C.]] He attended the [[Lyc\u00e9e Rochambeau]], a [[Education in France|French]] [[international school]] in the Washington suburb of [[Bethesda, Maryland]]. He went on to study History at the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] and then gained a Master's degree in [[International Relations]] at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref name=\"fb-connections\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fb-connections.org/mr-benedict-brogan|title=Mr Benedict Brogan &#124; Franco-British Connections|publisher=fb-connections.org|accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from Cambridge, Brogan worked at ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'' as a reporter in their [[Glasgow]] office. He worked in a wide range of roles at the ''Herald'', becoming their Political Correspondent based in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in [[London]] in 1992.<ref name=\"francobritishcouncil\">{{cite web|url=http://www.francobritishcouncil.org.uk/members.php?action=view&id=104|title=Members &middot; Franco-British Council|publisher=francobritishcouncil.org.uk|accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref> Brogan then worked for the ''[[Daily Mail]]'', moved to the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' in 2000, moved again to the ''Daily Mail'' as Political Editor in May 2005,<ref name=\"blogspot\">{{cite web|url=http://iaindale.blogspot.co.uk/2009/02/ben-brogan-rejoins-telegraph.html|title=Iain Dale's Diary: Ben Brogan Rejoins the Telegraph|publisher=iaindale.blogspot.co.uk|accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> and finally, in February 2009, re-joined the ''Telegraph'' as Assistant Editor and chief political commentator.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/feb/13/benedict-brogan-returns-to-telegraph|title=Benedict Brogan returns to Daily Telegraph|publisher=theguardian.com|accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nMedia commentator [[Iain Dale]] called the move ''\"a real coup for the ''Telegraph'' and a big blow to the ''Mail''. Brogan has proved himself to be one of the best political reporters in the business but in the last year or two he has also developed into a fine commentator\"'', and noted that the ''Daily Telegraph'', which at that point had an anti-[[David Cameron]] set of columnists, may have been trying to redress the balance.<ref name=\"blogspot\"/>\n\nBrogan wrote the \"Morning Briefing\" for the ''Telegraph'', a preview of the day ahead's political events, akin to [[Michael Allen (journalist)|Mike Allen]]'s ''Playbook''.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|url=http://pages.email.telegraph.co.uk/PoliticsSignUpPage|title=The Telegraph|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref> ''[[Total Politics]]'' referred to it as \"an important resource for fellow journalists and political junkies alike\".<ref name=\"totalpolitics\">{{cite web|url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/277577/top-100-political-journalists-2011.thtml|title=Top 100 political journalists 2011|publisher=totalpolitics.com|access-date=16 March 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301171422/http://www.totalpolitics.com/articles/277577/top-100-political-journalists-2011.thtml|archive-date=1 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBrogan maintained a blog on the ''Telegraph'' website; it billed itself as \"news, gossip, analysis, occasional insight into politics, and more\".<ref name=\"telegraph2\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/author/benedictbrogan|title=Benedict Brogan|publisher=blogs.telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' noted in 2008 that Brogan \"only turned his hand to blogging in 2006, but was an almost instant success and can now expect between 3,000 and 5,000 hits on a busy day. He describes his blog as the place where 'I empty my notebook', sharing snippets of news, observations and asides that might not otherwise find a place in his newspaper. He has won admirers across the political spectrum.\"<ref name=\"broganblog\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/search/simple.do?articleTypes=news&useHideArticle=true&sectionId=506&startYear=2010&searchString=Benedict+Brogan&startDay=1&useSectionFilter=true&sortOrder=desc&pageNumber=1&startMonth=1&destinationSectionUniqueName=search&pageLength=10&publicationName=ind&sortString=score|title=Benedict Brogan profile|publisher=independent.co.uk|accessdate=2 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June 2014, Brogan left his posts at ''The Telegraph''.<ref name=\"Sommers\"/> In December 2014, Brogan was appointed group director of [[public policy|public affairs]] at [[Lloyds Banking Group]].<ref name=PRWk1324440/>\n\n==Personal life==\nBrogan is married to [[Melanie Dawes]] and together they have a daughter.<ref name=\"bio - Women of the Year\">{{cite web|title=Women of the Year|url=http://www.womenoftheyear.co.uk/melanie-dawes/|access-date=14 November 2015|date=30 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117063201/http://www.womenoftheyear.co.uk/melanie-dawes/|archive-date=17 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dawes|first1=Melanie|title=International Women's Day \u2013 guest blog from Melanie Dawes|url=https://civilservice.blog.gov.uk/2015/03/16/international-womens-day/|website=Civil Service Blog|accessdate=14 November 2015|date=16 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=At Home with Lord Rothermere: Our Top Tax Man and the Non-Dom Press Baron|work=Private Eye|issue=1231|date=6 March 2009|quote=Dawes, a career Treasury civil servant said by some to have been drafted into HMRC to keep an eye on the taxmen, just happens to be married to Benedict Brogan}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Tony Gallagher]] | title=Deputy Editor of the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''| years=2009\u20132014| after=[[Allister Heath]]}}\n{{S-bef|before= David Hughes }}\n{{S-ttl|title= Political Editor of the ''Daily Mail''|years= May 2005 \u2013 March 2009}}\n{{S-aft|after= [[James Chapman (journalist)|James Chapman]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brogan, Benedict}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British people of French descent]]\n[[Category:University of Massachusetts Amherst alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:British political journalists]]\n[[Category:British columnists]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail journalists]]\n[[Category:Daily Telegraph journalists]]\n[[Category:Lloyds Banking Group people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               =  Benedict Brogan\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              =  <!-- filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" (or \"Image:\") prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  <!-- {{birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         =  <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| na