\n|Best Editing\n|Karl Sodersten\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Music Score\n|Paul Kelly\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=4|Ft. Lauderdale International Film Festival\n|Jury Award for Best Film\n|rowspan=2|Ray Lawrence\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Jury Award for Best Director\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Jury Award for Best Script\n|Andrew Bovell\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|colspan=2|Jury Award for Best Ensemble Cast\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=10|[[Inside Film Awards]]\n|colspan=2|Box Office Achievement\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Best Feature Film\n|Jan Chapman\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Ray Lawrence\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Best Direction\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Best Script\n|Andrew Bovell\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Best Actor\n|Anthony LaPaglia\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Best Actress\n|The ensemble female cast\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Best Cinematography\n|Mandy Walker\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Music\n|Paul Kelly\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Sound Design\n|Andrew Plain\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Nastro d'Argento|Italian National Syndicate of Film Journalists]]\n|Silver Ribbon for Best Foreign Director\n|Ray Lawrence\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[London Film Critics' Circle]] Awards\n|Film of the Year\n|Jan Chapman\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Screenwriter of the Year\n|Andrew Bovell\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|Actress of the Year\n|Kerry Armstrong\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Melbourne International Film Festival]] Award\n|Most Popular Feature Film\n|Ray Lawrence\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|National Board of Review, USA\n|colspan=2|Special Recognition for Excellence in Filmmaking\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival]]\n|Golden Seashell\n|Ray Lawrence\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cinema of Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0259393|title=Lantana}}\n*[https://archive.today/20121129152226/http://colsearch.nfsa.afc.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=yes;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=Number:488610;querytype=;rec=0;resCount=10 Lantana at the National Film and Sound Archive]\n*[https://www.ozmovies.com.au/movie/lantana Lantana] at [https://www.ozmovies.com.au Ozmovies]\n \n\n{{Ray Lawrence}}\n{{Paul Kelly}}\n{{Australian Film Institute Award for Best Film 1990-2009}}\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lantana (Film)}}\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award-winning albums]]\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:Australian drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Australian films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Australian writers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ray Lawrence]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Films set in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Paul Kelly (Australian musician)]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Adultery in films]]\n[[Category:Films about grieving]]\n[[Category:Hyperlink films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2001 film by Ray Lawrence}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Lantana\n| image          = Lantanaposter01.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Ray Lawrence (film director)|Ray Lawrence]]\n| producer       = [[Jan Chapman]]\n| screenplay      = [[Andrew Bovell]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''Speaking In Tongues'' (play)|Andrew Bovell}}\n| starring       = [[Anthony LaPaglia]]<br/> [[Geoffrey Rush]]<br/> [[Barbara Hershey]]<br/> [[Kerry Armstrong]]<br/> [[Rachael Blake (Australian actress)|Rachael Blake]]<br/> [[Vince Colosimo]]<br/> [[Russell Dykstra]]<br/> [[Daniela Farinacci]]<br/> [[Peter Phelps]]<br/> [[Leah Purcell]]<br/> [[Glenn Robbins]]\n| music          = [[Paul Kelly (Australian musician)|Paul Kelly]]\n| cinematography = [[Mandy Walker]] \n| editing        = Karl Sodersten\n| studio         =[[Australian Film Finance Corporation]]<br />MBP<br />[[New South Wales Film and Television Office]]<br />[[Jan Chapman|Jan Chapman Films]]\n| distributor     = [[Palace Films and Cinemas|Palace Films]]\n| released        = {{Film date|2001|7|8|[[Sydney Film Festival]]|df=yes}} \n| runtime        = 121 minutes<ref>http://www.classification.gov.au/Pages/View.aspx?sid=dvLr2Qbwbhw8mKYjFnlwkg%253d%253d&ncdctx=clejTJQCwz82Cfd7AgrHDNb8RGgqHQh1NB2utOMJvPUdzf2RrJqrFc4vuehryV%2b7</ref>\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = English\n| gross          = $15.7 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lantana.htm|title=Lantana (2001)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n'''''Lantana''''' is a 2001 [[Cinema of Australia|Australian]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]], directed by [[Ray Lawrence (film director)|Ray Lawrence]] and starring [[Anthony LaPaglia]], [[Kerry Armstrong]], [[Geoffrey Rush]] and [[Barbara Hershey]]. It is based on the play ''Speaking In Tongues'' by [[Andrew Bovell]], which premiered at Sydney's [[Griffin Theatre Company]]. The film won seven [[AACTA Awards]] including [[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]] and [[AACTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]].\n\n''Lantana'' is set in suburban [[Sydney]] and focuses on the complex relationships between the characters in the film. The central event of the film is the disappearance and death of a woman whose body is shown at the start of the film, but whose identity is not revealed until later. The film's name derives from the plant [[Lantana]], a weed prevalent in suburban Sydney.\n\n==Plot==\nA woman's body is shown in lantana bushes in a suburban garden.\n\nLeon, a policeman, and Jane have sex in a motel. They part, and Leon and his wife, Sonja, attend Latin dance classes that the recently separated Jane is also taking. Leon does not enjoy the classes. \n\nHe savagely beats an arrested drug dealer. He has emotional issues but refuses to confront or admit to them, while Sonja sees a therapist, Valerie, who has published a book on her daughter's recent murder. She and her husband, John, barely speak; he refers to their marriage as surviving on their grief. Valerie feels threatened by another patient, Patrick, who is having an affair with a married man, forcing her to confront her marital issues.\n\nJane purposely encounters Leon outside his station, and they have sex despite his reservations. Nik is upset at the relationship because he is friends with her estranged husband, Pete, who wants to return home. Jane pairs with Sonja in the next salsa class, angering Leon, who ends their arrangement, upsetting Jane. She invites Nik for coffee at Paula's behest, with whom she is friendly, and offers him money as they are struggling. Paula now starts disliking Jane.\n\nValerie, coming home late, crashes. Stranded, she calls John, unsuccessfully. She hails a vehicle but never makes it home. Leon is the investigating detective and searches her office. Surprised at seeing his wife's details, he takes a recording of their sessions, from which he learns that Sonja would not consider an affair a betrayal, but would if Leon didn't tell her. Leon arrives home late, but Sonja is awake. He asks her about her therapy. They discuss their relationship, and he says he just ended an affair but still loves her. Sonja is upset and feels betrayed. Leon sleeps on the couch. In the morning, Sonja says that he will be lucky if she returns home that night.\n\nLeon goes to John's house as he is the main suspect in his wife's disappearance. Leon starts discussing love, marriage and affairs, but lies to John when asked if he ever had an affair. Leon goes to Jane's house after she calls the police. Jane, late one night, saw Nik arrive home and throw something in the bushes. Later, she finds a woman's shoe there. Leon and Paula arrive and declare the shoe is Valerie's.\n\nThe police arrest Nik and he leaves his children with Jane. Police summon Paula for questioning. Neither Nik nor Paula knows that Jane called the police. Although Paula dislikes Jane, she thanks her for minding their children. The police interrogate Nik, but he refuses to answer questions about Valerie, repeatedly asking for Paula. Afterwards, Nik relaxes and talks with Leon and Paula. Valerie had car trouble and hailed Nik. He agreed to take her home but she panicked when he took a shortcut and jumped out, leaving her shoe. Paula goes to Jane's house for her children, where she tells her that Nik is innocent. Jane asks how she knows, and Paula says he told her. Jane asks if she can spend more time with the kids, but Paula forbids it after seeing how Jane went into her house and tidied it. Leon, Paula, Nik, and John go to where Valerie jumped out of the truck. They find her body, as she had fallen down a ravine. Leon listens to the rest of the therapy tape, where his wife says that she still loved him, and cries.\n\nLeon returns home and sees his wife outside. Jane salsa dances alone, drinking and smoking, and her husband leaves her. Patrick is pained to see his lover spending time with his wife and kids. Nik and Paula are spending time with their kids. The movie ends with Sonja and Leon dancing seductively. Leon, who found dancing with his wife difficult, now looks into Sonja's eyes and dances, just as she wanted. Sonja struggles to initially return Leon's gaze but does as the movie ends.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Anthony LaPaglia]] as Detective Leon Zat\n*[[Geoffrey Rush]] as John Knox\n*[[Barbara Hershey]] as Valerie Somers\n*[[Kerry Armstrong]] as Sonja Zat\n*[[Rachael Blake (Australian actress)|Rachael Blake]] as Jane O'May\n*[[Vince Colosimo]] as Nik D'Amato\n*[[Russell Dykstra]] as Neil Toohey\n*[[Daniella Farinacci]] as Paula D'Amato\n*[[Peter Phelps]] as Patrick Phelan\n*[[Leah Purcell]] as Claudia Weis\n*[[Glenn Robbins]] as Pete O'May\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nLantana opened on October 4, 2001 in Australia and December 14, 2001 in North America in 6 theaters. In the US, it grossed $66,701 with an average of $11,116 per theater and ranking #39 at the box office. Its widest release was 108 theaters and it ended up earning $4,623,189. The film earned $11,124,261 internationally (including $6,125,907 in Australia) for a total of $15,747,450.<ref>https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lantana.htm</ref><ref>https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=lantana.htm</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Lantana'' received positive reviews from critics and has a 'certified fresh' score of 90% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 105 reviews with an average rating of 7.38/10. The critical consensus states \"Lantana is an intricately plotted character study that quietly shines with authenticity.\"<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lantana/</ref> The film also has a score of 84 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]] based on 29 critics indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>http://www.metacritic.com/movie/lantana</ref>\n\nWriter and critic [[Roger Ebert]] compared the film to ''[[Short Cuts]]'' and ''[[Magnolia (film)|Magnolia]]'' in terms of how it developed the connections between the lives of strangers.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20020118/REVIEWS/201180303/1023 | title=Lantana |work=Chicago Sun=Times | first=Roger | last=Ebert | date=18 January 2002}}</ref> It premiered in the UK on [[Channel 4]] in December 2006. British critic [[Philip French]] described the film as a \"thoughtful, gripping movie\" based around the themes of \"trust in its various forms, betrayal, forgiveness and grief\".<ref name=\"ObsFrench\">{{cite news|last=French|first=Philip|title=Aye, there's the shrub|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/aug/18/philipfrench|work=The Observer |accessdate=28 December 2010|location=London|date=18 August 2002}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=16|[[AACTA Awards]]<br><small>(2001 AFI Awards)</small>\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|[[Jan Chapman]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Director]]\n|[[Ray Lawrence (film director)|